# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: aircraft-navigation
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:aircraft-navigation/air-navigation] The basic principles of **air navigation** are similar to those of general navigation, involving the planning, recording, and controlling of a craft’s movement from one location to another.
[src:aircraft-navigation/air-navigation] In aviation, navigation plays a critical role in ensuring that aircraft operate safely and efficiently within controlled airspace and along designated routes, in accordance with international standards.
[src:aircraft-navigation/air-navigation] Successful air navigation involves piloting an aircraft from place to place without getting lost, not breaking the laws applying to aircraft, or endangering the safety of those on board or on the ground.
[src:aircraft-navigation/air-navigation] Air navigation differs from the navigation of surface craft in several ways; aircraft travel at relatively high speeds, leaving less time to calculate their position en route.
[src:aircraft-navigation/air-navigation] Aircraft normally cannot stop in mid-air to ascertain their position at leisure.
[src:aircraft-navigation/air-navigation] Aircraft are safety-limited by the amount of fuel they can carry; a surface vehicle can usually get lost, run out of fuel, then simply await rescue.
[src:aircraft-navigation/air-navigation] There is no in-flight rescue for most aircraft.
[src:aircraft-navigation/air-navigation] Additionally, collisions with obstructions are usually fatal.
[src:aircraft-navigation/air-navigation] Therefore, constant awareness of position is critical for aircraft pilots.
[src:aircraft-navigation/air-navigation] The techniques used for navigation in the air will depend on whether the aircraft is flying under visual flight rules (VFR) or instrument flight rules (IFR).
[src:aircraft-navigation/air-navigation] In the latter case, the pilot will navigate exclusively using instruments and radio navigation aids such as beacons, or as directed under radar control by air traffic control.
[src:aircraft-navigation/air-navigation] In the former case, a pilot will largely navigate using "dead reckoning" combined with visual observations (known as pilotage), with reference to appropriate maps.
[src:aircraft-navigation/air-navigation] This may be supplemented using radio navigation aids or satellite based positioning systems.
[src:aircraft-navigation/air-navigation] The first step in navigation is deciding where one wishes to go.
[src:aircraft-navigation/air-navigation] A private pilot planning a flight under VFR will usually use an aeronautical chart of the area which is published specifically for the use of pilots.
[src:aircraft-navigation/air-navigation] This map will depict controlled airspace, radio navigation aids and airfields prominently, as well as hazards to flying such as mountains, tall radio masts, etc.
[src:aircraft-navigation/air-navigation] It also includes sufficient ground detail – towns, roads, wooded areas – to aid visual navigation.
[src:aircraft-navigation/air-navigation] In the UK, the CAA publishes a series of maps covering the whole of the UK at various scales, updated annually.
[src:aircraft-navigation/air-navigation] The information is also updated in the notices to airmen, or NOTAMs.
[src:aircraft-navigation/air-navigation] The pilot will choose a route, taking care to avoid controlled airspace that is not permitted for the flight, restricted areas, danger areas and so on.
[src:aircraft-navigation/air-navigation] The chosen route is plotted on the map, and the lines drawn are called the *track*.
[src:aircraft-navigation/air-navigation] The aim of all subsequent navigation is to follow the chosen track as accurately as possible.
[src:aircraft-navigation/air-navigation] Occasionally, the pilot may elect on one leg to follow a clearly visible feature on the ground such as a railway track, river, highway, or coast.
[src:aircraft-navigation/air-navigation] When an aircraft is in flight, it is moving relative to the body of air through which it is flying; therefore maintaining an accurate ground track is not as easy as it might appear, unless there is no wind at all—a very rare occurrence.
[src:aircraft-navigation/air-navigation] The pilot must adjust heading to compensate for the wind, in order to follow the ground track.
[src:aircraft-navigation/air-navigation] Initially the pilot will calculate headings to fly for each leg of the trip prior to departure, using the forecast wind directions and speeds supplied by the meteorological authorities for the purpose.
[src:aircraft-navigation/air-navigation] These figures are generally accurate and updated several times per day, but the unpredictable nature of the weather means that the pilot must be prepared to make further adjustments in flight.
[src:aircraft-navigation/air-navigation] A general aviation (GA) pilot will often make use of either a flight computer – a type of slide rule – or a purpose-designed electronic navigational computer to calculate initial headings.
[src:aircraft-navigation/air-navigation] The primary instrument of navigation is the magnetic compass.
[src:aircraft-navigation/air-navigation] The needle or card aligns itself to magnetic north, which does not coincide with true north, so the pilot must also allow for this, called the magnetic variation (or declination).
[src:aircraft-navigation/air-navigation] The variation that applies locally is also shown on the flight map.
[src:aircraft-navigation/air-navigation] Once the pilot has calculated the actual headings required, the next step is to calculate the flight times for each leg.
[src:aircraft-navigation/air-navigation] This is necessary to perform accurate dead reckoning.
[src:aircraft-navigation/air-navigation] The pilot also needs to take into account the slower initial airspeed during climb to calculate the time to top of climb.
[src:aircraft-navigation/air-navigation] It is also helpful to calculate the top of descent, or the point at which the pilot would plan to commence the descent for landing.
[src:aircraft-navigation/air-navigation] The flight time will depend on both the desired cruising speed of the aircraft, and the wind – a tailwind will shorten flight times, a headwind will increase them.
[src:aircraft-navigation/air-navigation] The flight computer has scales to help pilots compute these easily.
[src:aircraft-navigation/air-navigation] The point of no return, sometimes referred to as the PNR, is the point on a flight at which a plane has just enough fuel, plus any mandatory reserve, to return to the airfield from which it departed.
[src:aircraft-navigation/air-navigation] Beyond this point that option is closed, and the plane must proceed to some other destination.
[src:aircraft-navigation/air-navigation] Alternatively, with respect to a large region without airfields, e.g. an ocean, it can mean the point before which it is closer to turn around and after which it is closer to continue.
[src:aircraft-navigation/air-navigation] Similarly, the Equal time point, referred to as the ETP (also critical point), is the point in the flight where it would take the same time to continue flying straight, or track back to the departure aerodrome.
[src:aircraft-navigation/air-navigation] The ETP is not dependent on fuel, but wind, giving a change in ground speed out from, and back to the departure aerodrome.
[src:aircraft-navigation/air-navigation] In Nil wind conditions, the ETP is located halfway between the two aerodromes, but in reality it is shifted depending on the windspeed and direction.
[src:aircraft-navigation/air-navigation] The aircraft that is flying across the Ocean for example, would be required to calculate ETPs for one engine inoperative, depressurization, and a normal ETP; all of which could actually be different points along the route.
[src:aircraft-navigation/air-navigation] For example, in one engine inoperative and depressurization situations the aircraft would be forced to lower operational altitudes, which would affect its fuel consumption, cruise speed and ground speed.
[src:aircraft-navigation/air-navigation] Each situation therefore would have a different ETP.
[src:aircraft-navigation/air-navigation] Commercial aircraft are not allowed to operate along a route that is out of range of a suitable place to land if an emergency such as an engine failure occurs.
[src:aircraft-navigation/air-navigation] The ETP calculations serve as a planning strategy, so flight crews always have an 'out' in an emergency event, allowing a safe diversion to their chosen alternate.
[src:aircraft-navigation/air-navigation] The final stage is to note which areas the route will pass through or over, and to make a note of all of the things to be done – which ATC units to contact, the appropriate frequencies, visual reporting points, and so on.
[src:aircraft-navigation/air-navigation] It is also important to note which pressure setting regions will be entered, so that the pilot can ask for the QNH (air pressure) of those regions.
[src:aircraft-navigation/air-navigation] Finally, the pilot should have in mind some alternative plans in case the route cannot be flown for some reason – unexpected weather conditions being the most common.
[src:aircraft-navigation/air-navigation] At times the pilot may be required to file a flight plan for an alternate destination and to carry adequate fuel for this.
[src:aircraft-navigation/air-navigation] The more work a pilot can do on the ground prior to departure, the easier it will be in the air.
[src:aircraft-navigation/air-navigation] IFR pilots may fly on other routes but they then must perform all such calculations themselves; the LSALT calculation is the most difficult.
[src:aircraft-navigation/air-navigation] The pilot then needs to look at the weather and minimum specifications for landing at the destination airport and the alternate requirements.
[src:aircraft-navigation/air-navigation] Pilots must also comply with all the rules including their legal ability to use a particular instrument approach depending on how recently they last performed one.
[src:aircraft-navigation/air-navigation] In recent years, strict beacon-to-beacon flight paths have started to be replaced by routes derived through performance-based navigation (PBN) techniques.
[src:aircraft-navigation/air-navigation] When operators develop flight plans for their aircraft, the PBN approach encourages them to assess the overall accuracy, integrity, availability, continuity, and functionality of the aggregate navigation aids present within the applicable airspace.
[src:aircraft-navigation/air-navigation] Once these determinations have been made, the operator develops a route that is the most time and fuel efficient while respecting all applicable safety concerns—thereby maximizing both the aircraft's and the airspace's overall performance capabilities.
[src:aircraft-navigation/air-navigation] Under the PBN approach, technologies evolve over time (e.g., ground beacons become satellite beacons) without requiring the underlying aircraft operation to be recalculated.
[src:aircraft-navigation/air-navigation] Also, navigation specifications used to assess the sensors and equipment that are available in an airspace can be cataloged and shared to inform equipment upgrade decisions and the ongoing harmonization of the world's various air navigation systems.
[src:aircraft-navigation/air-navigation] Once in flight, the pilot must take pains to stick to plan, otherwise getting lost is all too easy.
[src:aircraft-navigation/air-navigation] This is especially true if flying in the dark or over featureless terrain.
[src:aircraft-navigation/air-navigation] This means that the pilot must stick to the calculated headings, heights and speeds as accurately as possible, unless flying under visual flight rules.
[src:aircraft-navigation/air-navigation] The visual pilot must regularly compare the ground with the map, (pilotage) to ensure that the track is being followed although adjustments are generally calculated and planned.
[src:aircraft-navigation/air-navigation] Usually, the pilot will fly for some time as planned to a point where features on the ground are easily recognised.
[src:aircraft-navigation/air-navigation] If the wind is different from that expected, the pilot must adjust heading accordingly, but this is not done by guesswork, but by mental calculation – often using the 1 in 60 rule.
[src:aircraft-navigation/air-navigation] For example, a two degree error at the halfway stage can be corrected by adjusting heading by four degrees the other way to arrive in position at the end of the leg.
[src:aircraft-navigation/air-navigation] This is also a point to reassess the estimated time for the leg.
[src:aircraft-navigation/air-navigation] A good pilot will become adept at applying a variety of techniques to stay on track.
[src:aircraft-navigation/air-navigation] While the compass is the primary instrument used to determine one's heading, pilots will usually refer instead to the direction indicator (DI), a gyroscopically driven device which is much more stable than a compass.
[src:aircraft-navigation/air-navigation] The compass reading will be used to correct for any drift (precession) of the DI periodically.
[src:aircraft-navigation/air-navigation] The compass itself will only show a steady reading when the aircraft has been in straight and level flight long enough to allow it to settle.
[src:aircraft-navigation/air-navigation] Should the pilot be unable to complete a leg – for example bad weather arises, or the visibility falls below the minima permitted by the pilot's license, the pilot must *divert* to another route.
[src:aircraft-navigation/air-navigation] Since this is an unplanned leg, the pilot must be able to mentally calculate suitable headings to give the desired new track.
[src:aircraft-navigation/air-navigation] Using the flight computer in flight is usually impractical, so mental techniques to give rough and ready results are used.
[src:aircraft-navigation/air-navigation] The wind is usually allowed for by assuming that sine A = A, for angles less than 60° (when expressed in terms of a fraction of 60° – e.g.
[src:aircraft-navigation/air-navigation] A method for computing this mentally is the clock code.
[src:aircraft-navigation/air-navigation] However the pilot must be extra vigilant when flying diversions to maintain awareness of position.
[src:aircraft-navigation/air-navigation] Some diversions can be temporary – for example to skirt around a local storm cloud.
[src:aircraft-navigation/air-navigation] In such cases, the pilot can turn 60 degrees away his desired heading for a given period of time.
[src:aircraft-navigation/air-navigation] Once clear of the storm, he can then turn back in the opposite direction 120 degrees, and fly this heading for the same length of time.
[src:aircraft-navigation/air-navigation] This is a 'wind-star' maneuver and, with no winds aloft, will place him back on his original track with his trip time increased by the length of one diversion leg.
[src:aircraft-navigation/air-navigation] Another reason for not relying on the magnetic compass during flight, apart from calibrating the Heading indicator from time to time, is because magnetic compasses are subject to errors caused by flight conditions and other internal and external interferences on the magnet system.
[src:aircraft-navigation/air-navigation] Many GA aircraft are fitted with a variety of navigation aids, such as Automatic direction finder (ADF), inertial navigation, compasses, radar navigation, VHF omnidirectional range (VOR) and Global navigation satellite system (GNSS).
[src:aircraft-navigation/air-navigation] ADF uses non-directional beacons (NDBs) on the ground to drive a display which shows the direction of the beacon from the aircraft.
[src:aircraft-navigation/air-navigation] The pilot may use this bearing to draw a line on the map to show the bearing from the beacon.
[src:aircraft-navigation/air-navigation] By using a second beacon, two lines may be drawn to locate the aircraft at the intersection of the lines.
[src:aircraft-navigation/air-navigation] NDBs also can give erroneous readings because they use very long wavelengths, which are easily bent and reflected by ground features and the atmosphere.
[src:aircraft-navigation/air-navigation] NDBs continue to be used as a common form of navigation in some countries with relatively few navigational aids.
[src:aircraft-navigation/air-navigation] VOR is a more sophisticated system, and is still the primary air navigation system established for aircraft flying under IFR in those countries with many navigational aids.
[src:aircraft-navigation/air-navigation] In this system, a beacon emits a specially modulated signal which consists of two sine waves which are out of phase.
[src:aircraft-navigation/air-navigation] The phase difference corresponds to the actual bearing relative to magnetic north (in some cases true north) that the receiver is from the station.
[src:aircraft-navigation/air-navigation] The upshot is that the receiver can determine with certainty the exact bearing from the station.
[src:aircraft-navigation/air-navigation] Again, a cross-cut is used to pinpoint the location.
[src:aircraft-navigation/air-navigation] Many VOR stations also have additional equipment called DME (distance measuring equipment) which will allow a suitable receiver to determine the exact distance from the station.
[src:aircraft-navigation/air-navigation] Together with the bearing, this allows an exact position to be determined from a single beacon alone.
[src:aircraft-navigation/air-navigation] For convenience, some VOR stations also transmit local weather information which the pilot can listen in to, perhaps generated by an Automated Surface Observing System.
[src:aircraft-navigation/air-navigation] A VOR which is co-located with a DME is usually a component of a TACAN.
[src:aircraft-navigation/air-navigation] Prior to the advent of GNSS, **Celestial Navigation** was also used by trained navigators.
[src:aircraft-navigation/air-navigation] This was especially true on military bombers and transport aircraft in the event of all electronic navigational aids being turned off in time of war.
[src:aircraft-navigation/air-navigation] Originally navigators used an astrodome and regular sextant or bubble octant but the more streamlined periscopic sextant was used from the 1940s to the 1990s.
[src:aircraft-navigation/air-navigation] From the 1970s airliners used inertial navigation systems, especially on inter-continental routes, until the shooting down of Korean Air Lines Flight 007 in 1983 prompted the US government to make GPS available for civilian use.
[src:aircraft-navigation/air-navigation] Finally, an aircraft may be supervised from the ground using surveillance information from e.g. radar or multilateration.
[src:aircraft-navigation/air-navigation] ATC can then feed back information to the pilot to help establish position, or can actually tell the pilot the position of the aircraft, depending on the level of ATC service the pilot is receiving.
[src:aircraft-navigation/air-navigation] The use of GNSS in aircraft is becoming increasingly common.
[src:aircraft-navigation/air-navigation] GNSS provides very precise aircraft position, altitude, heading and ground speed information.
[src:aircraft-navigation/air-navigation] GNSS makes navigation precision once reserved to large RNAV-equipped aircraft available to the GA pilot.
[src:aircraft-navigation/air-navigation] Recently, many airports include GNSS instrument approaches.
[src:aircraft-navigation/air-navigation] GNSS approaches consist of either overlays to existing precision and non-precision approaches or stand-alone GNSS approaches.
[src:aircraft-navigation/air-navigation] Approaches having the lowest decision heights generally require that GNSS be augmented by a second system—e.g., the FAA's Wide Area Augmentation System (WAAS).
[src:aircraft-navigation/air-navigation] Civilian flight navigators (a mostly redundant aircrew position, also called 'air navigator' or 'flight navigator'), were employed on older aircraft, typically between the late-1910s and the 1970s.
[src:aircraft-navigation/air-navigation] The crew member, occasionally two navigation crew members for some flights, was responsible for the trip navigation, including its dead reckoning and celestial navigation.
[src:aircraft-navigation/air-navigation] This was especially essential when trips were flown over oceans or other large bodies of water, where radio navigation aids were not originally available.
[src:aircraft-navigation/air-navigation] (Satellite coverage is now provided worldwide).
[src:aircraft-navigation/air-navigation] As the installation of electronic navigation systems into the Captain's and FO's instrument panels was relatively straight forward, the navigator's position in commercial aviation (but not necessarily military aviation) became redundant.
[src:aircraft-navigation/air-navigation] (Some countries task their air forces to fly without navigation aids during wartime, thus still requiring a navigator's position).
[src:aircraft-navigation/air-navigation] Most civilian air navigators were retired or made redundant by the early 1980s.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] ADS-B is "automatic" in that it requires no pilot or external input to trigger its transmissions.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] It is "dependent" in that it depends on data from the aircraft's navigation system to provide the transmitted data.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] ADS-B is a key part of the International Civil Aviation Organization's (ICAO) approved aviation surveillance technologies and is being progressively incorporated into national airspaces worldwide.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] For example, it is an element of the United States Next Generation Air Transportation System (NextGen), the Single European Sky ATM Research project (SESAR), and India's Aviation System Block Upgrade (ASBU).
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] Canada uses ADS-B for surveillance in remote regions not covered by traditional radar (areas around Hudson Bay, the Labrador Sea, Davis Strait, Baffin Bay and southern Greenland) since 15 January 2009.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] Aircraft operators are encouraged to install ADS-B products that are interoperable with US and European standards, and Canadian air traffic controllers can provide better and more fuel-efficient flight routes when operators can be tracked via ADS-B.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] ADS-B is an airspace surveillance system which could eventually replace secondary surveillance radar as the main surveillance method for controlling aircraft worldwide.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] In the United States ADS-B is an integral component of the NextGen national airspace strategy for upgrading and enhancing aviation infrastructure and operations.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] ADS-B enhances safety by making an aircraft visible, in realtime, to air traffic control (ATC) and to other ADS-B In equipped aircraft, with position and velocity data transmitted every second.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] FAA program descriptions state that ADS-B Out broadcasts position and other data (such as altitude and ground speed) once per second to ground stations and other aircraft, and note that U.S. airspace and equipment-performance requirements are specified in 14 CFR §§ 91.225 and 91.227.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] Other uses of ADS-B data include post-flight analysis, inexpensive flight tracking, planning, and dispatch.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] Within the United States, the ADS-B system has the ability to provide air traffic and government-generated graphical weather information at no cost through TIS-B and FIS-B applications.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] ADS-B consists of two distinct functions - "ADS-B Out" and "ADS-B In".
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] Each "ADS-B Out" aircraft periodically broadcasts information about itself, such as identification, current position, altitude and velocity through an onboard transmitter.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] ADS-B Out provides air traffic controllers with real-time aircraft position information that is, in most cases, more accurate than the information available with current radar-based systems.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] With more accurate information, ATC can manage and separate aircraft with improved precision and timing.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] "ADS-B In" is the reception and processing of transmitted ADS-B information (i.e.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] In the US ADS-B In can also include other information for pilots transmitted from ATC ground stations such as FIS-B and TIS-B data.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] These ground station data broadcasts are typically made available only when an ADS-B Out broadcasting aircraft is nearby.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] The ADS-B Out system relies on two avionics components aboard each aircraft: a high-integrity satellite navigation source (i.e.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] GPS or other certified GNSS receiver) and a datalink (the ADS-B unit).
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] There are several types of certified ADS-B data links, but the most common ones operate at 1090 MHz, essentially a modified Mode S transponder, or at 978 MHz.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] The FAA would like to see aircraft that operate exclusively below 18,000 feet (5,500 m) use the 978 MHz link, as this will alleviate congestion of the 1090 MHz frequency.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] To obtain ADS-B Out capability at 1090 MHz, user-operators can install a new transponder or modify an existing transponder if the manufacturer offers an ADS-B upgrade (plus install a certified GNSS position source if one is not already present).
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] ADS-B provides many benefits to both pilots and air traffic control that improve both the safety and efficiency of flight.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] When using an *ADS-B In* system, a pilot is able to view traffic information about surrounding aircraft if those aircraft are equipped with ADS-B Out.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] This information includes altitude, heading, speed, and distance to the aircraft.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] In addition to receiving position reports from ADS-B Out participants, in the US, TIS-B can provide position reports on non-ADS-B Out-equipped aircraft if suitable ground equipment and ground radar exist.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] ADS-R re-transmits ADS-B position reports between UAT and 1090 MHz frequency bands.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] ADS-B ground stations are significantly cheaper to install and operate compared to primary and secondary radar systems used by air traffic control for aircraft separation and control.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] Unlike some alternative in-flight weather services currently being offered commercially, there will be no subscription fees to use ADS-B services or its various benefits in the US.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] The aircraft owner will pay for the equipment and installation, while the Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) will pay for administering and broadcasting all the services related to the technology.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] ADS-B makes flying significantly safer for the aviation community by providing pilots with improved situational awareness.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] Pilots in an ADS-B In equipped cockpit will have the ability to see, on their in-cockpit flight display, other traffic operating in the airspace and have access to clear and detailed weather information.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] They will also be able to receive pertinent updates ranging from temporary flight restrictions to runway closings.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] Even aircraft only equipped with ADS-B Out will benefit from air traffic controllers' ability to more accurately and reliably monitor their position.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] When using this system both pilots and controllers will see the same radar picture.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] Other fully equipped aircraft using the airspace around them will be able to more easily identify and avoid conflict with an aircraft equipped with ADS-B Out.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] With past systems such as the Traffic alert and Collision Avoidance System (TCAS) aircraft could only see other aircraft equipped with the same technology.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] With ADS-B, information is sent to aircraft using ADS-B In, which displays all aircraft in the area, provided those aircraft are equipped with ADS-B Out.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] ADS-B provides better surveillance in fringe areas of radar coverage.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] ADS-B does not have the siting limitations of radar.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] Its accuracy is consistent throughout the range.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] In both forms of ADS-B (1090ES & 978 MHz UAT), the position report is updated once per second.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] The 978 MHz UAT provides the information in a single, short-duration transmission.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] The 1090ES system transmits two different kinds of position reports (even/odd) randomly.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] To decode the position unambiguously, one position report of both kinds or a reference position nearby is needed.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] ADS-B technology provides a more accurate report of an aircraft's position.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] This allows controllers to guide aircraft into and out of crowded airspace with smaller separation standards than it was previously possible to do safely.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] This reduces the amount of time aircraft must spend waiting for clearances, being vectored for spacing and holding.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] Estimates show that this is already having a beneficial impact by reducing pollution and fuel consumption.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] The ADS-B data link supports a number of airborne and ground applications.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] A cockpit display of traffic information (CDTI) is a generic display that provides the flight crew with surveillance information about other aircraft, including their position.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] Traffic information for a CDTI may be obtained from one or multiple sources, including ADS-B, TCAS, and TIS-B.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] In addition to traffic based on ADS-B reports, a CDTI function might also display current weather conditions, terrain, airspace structure, obstructions, detailed airport maps, and other information relevant to the particular phase of flight.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] ADS-B is seen as a valuable technology to enhance airborne collision avoidance system (ACAS) operation.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] Eventually, the ACAS function may be provided based solely on ADS-B, without requiring active interrogations of other aircraft transponders.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] Aircraft with transponder only, or no transponder capability at all will not be shown.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] Pilots who become complacent or overconfident in this system are thus a safety problem, not only for themselves but for other transponder-only aircraft, and glider aircraft without ADS-B transponder.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] Glider aircraft often use the FLARM system for collision avoidance with other glider aircraft, but this system is not compatible with ADS-B.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] Aircraft with ADS-B but without FLARM are thus a safety risk for gliders with FLARM but without ADS-B and vice versa.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] Some aircraft, like those used for towing gliders, have both FLARM and ADS-B transponders for this reason.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] A security researcher claimed in 2012 that ADS-B has no defence against being interfered with via spoofed ADS-B messages because they were neither encrypted nor authenticated.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] The FAA responded to this criticism saying that they were aware of the issues and risks but were unable to disclose how they are mitigated as that is classified.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] A possible mitigation is multilateration to verify that the claimed position is close to the position from which the message was broadcast.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] Here the timing of received messages is compared to establish distances from the antenna to the plane.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] The lack of any authentication within the standard makes it mandatory to validate any received data by use of the primary radar.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] Because the content of ADS-B messages is not encrypted, it may be read by anybody.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] The ADS-B system has three main components: 1) ground infrastructure, 2) airborne component, and 3) operating procedures.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] The source of the state vector and other transmitted information as well as user applications are not considered to be part of the ADS-B system.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] Two link solutions are used as the physical layer for relaying ADS-B position reports: universal access transceiver, and 1090 MHz extended squitter.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] A universal access transceiver is a data link on the frequency 978 MHz.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] UAT is intended to serve the majority of the general aviation community in the United States.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] The data link is approved in the Federal Aviation Administration's "final rule" for use in all airspace except class A (above 18,000 ft.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] UAT is intended to support not only ADS-B, but also flight information service – broadcast (FIS-B), traffic information service – broadcast (TIS-B), and, if required in the future, supplementary ranging and positioning capabilities.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] Due to the set of standards required for this rule, it is seen as the most effective application for general aviation users.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] UAT will allow aircraft equipped with "out" broadcast capabilities to be seen by any other aircraft using ADS-B In technology as well as by FAA ground stations.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] Aircraft equipped with ADS-B In technology will be able to see detailed altitude and vector information from other ADS-B Out equipped aircraft as well as FIS-B and TIS-B broadcasts.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] These broadcasts serve to provide early adopters of the technology with benefits as an incentive for more pilots to use the technology before 2020.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] Aircraft receiving traffic information through the TIS-B service will see other aircraft in a manner that is similar to how all aircraft will be seen after they have been equipped by 2020.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] The availability of a non-subscription weather information service, FIS-B, provides general aviation users with a useful alternative to other monthly or annual fee-based services.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] The UAT system is specifically designed for ADS-B operation.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] UAT is also the first link to be certified for "radar-like" ATC services in the United States.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] Since 2001 it has been providing 5 nmi (9.3 km; 5.8 mi) en-route separation (the same as mosaic radar but not 3 nmi (5.6 km; 3.5 mi) of single-site sensors) in Alaska.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] UAT-equipped aircraft can also observe each other directly with high accuracy and minimal latency.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] Viable ADS-B UAT networks are being installed as part of the United States' NextGen air traffic system.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] In 2002 the Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) announced a dual-link decision using the 1090 MHz extended squitter (1090 ES) link for air carrier and private or commercial operators of high-performance aircraft, and universal access transceiver link for the typical general aviation user.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] In November 2012, the European Aviation Safety Agency confirmed that the European Union would also use 1090 ES for interoperability.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] The format of extended squitter messages has been codified by the ICAO.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] With 1090 ES, the existing Mode S transponder (TSO C-112 or a standalone 1090 MHz transmitter) supports a message type known as the extended squitter message.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] It is a periodic message that provides position, velocity, time, and, in the future, intent.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] The basic ES does not offer intent since current flight management systems do not provide such data (called trajectory change points).
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] To enable an aircraft to send an extended squitter message, the transponder is modified (TSO C-166A) and aircraft position and other status information is routed to the transponder.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] ATC ground stations and aircraft equipped with traffic collision avoidance system (TCAS) already have the necessary 1090 MHz (Mode S) receivers to receive these signals, and would only require enhancements to accept and process the additional extended squitter information.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] As per the FAA ADS-B link decision, and the technical link standards, 1090 ES does not support FIS-B service.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] Radar directly measures the range and bearing of an aircraft from a ground-based antenna.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] The primary surveillance radar is usually a pulse radar.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] It continuously transmits high-power radio frequency (RF) pulses.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] Bearing is measured by the position of the rotating radar antenna when it receives the RF pulses that are reflected from the aircraft skin.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] The range is measured by measuring the time it takes for the RF energy to travel to and from the aircraft.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] Primary surveillance radar does not require any cooperation from the aircraft.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] It is robust in the sense that surveillance outage failure modes are limited to those associated with the ground radar system.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] Secondary surveillance radar depends on active replies from the aircraft.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] Its failure modes include the transponder aboard the aircraft.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] Typical ADS-B aircraft installations use the output of the navigation unit for navigation and for cooperative surveillance, introducing a common failure mode that must be accommodated in air traffic surveillance systems.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] The radiated beam becomes wider as the distance between the antenna and the aircraft becomes greater, making the position information less accurate.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] Additionally, detecting changes in aircraft velocity requires several radar sweeps that are spaced several seconds apart.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] In contrast, a system using ADS-B creates and listens for periodic position and intent reports from aircraft.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] These reports are generated based on the aircraft's navigation system and distributed via one or more of the ADS-B data links.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] The accuracy of the data is no longer susceptible to the position of the aircraft or the length of time between radar sweeps.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] When the aircraft is farther away, the weaker received signal will tend to be more affected by the aforementioned adverse factors and is less likely to be received without errors.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] Error detection will allow errors to be recognized, so the system maintains full accuracy regardless of aircraft position when the signal can be received and decoded correctly.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] Today's air traffic control (ATC) systems do not rely on coverage by a single radar.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] Instead, a multi-radar picture is presented via the ATC system's display to the controller.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] This improves the quality of the reported position of the aircraft, provides a measure of redundancy, and makes it possible to verify the output of the different radars against others.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] ADS-A is based on a negotiated one-to-one peer relationship between an aircraft providing ADS information and a ground facility requiring receipt of ADS messages.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] For example, ADS-A reports are employed in the Future Air Navigation System (FANS) using the Aircraft Communications Addressing and Reporting System (ACARS) as the communication protocol.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] Traffic information service – broadcast (TIS–B) supplements ADS-B's air-to-air services to provide complete situational awareness in the cockpit of all traffic known to the ATC system.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] TIS–B is an important service for an ADS-B link in airspace where not all aircraft are transmitting ADS-B information.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] The ground TIS–B station transmits surveillance target information on the ADS-B data link for unequipped targets or targets transmitting only on another ADS-B link.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] The multilink gateway service is a companion to TIS-B for achieving interoperability between different aircraft equipped with 1090ES or UAT by using ground-based relay stations.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] These aircraft cannot directly share air-to-air ADS-B data due to the different communication frequencies.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] In terminal areas, where both types of ADS-B link are in use, ADS-B/TIS-B ground stations use ground-to-air broadcasts to relay ADS-B reports received on one link to aircraft using the other link.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] Because of the issues with multilink, many ADS-B manufacturers are designing ADS-B systems as dual-frequency capable.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] FIS-B provides weather text, weather graphics, NOTAMs, ATIS, and similar information.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] FIS-B is inherently different from ADS-B in that it requires sources of data external to the aircraft or broadcasting unit, and has different performance requirements such as periodicity of broadcast.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] In the United States, FIS-B services are provided over the UAT link in areas that have a ground surveillance infrastructure.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] Another potential aircraft-based broadcast capability is to transmit aircraft measurements of meteorological data.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] Airservices Australia operates more than 70 ADS-B ground receiver sites and Australia has full continental ADS-B coverage above FL300 (30,000 feet).
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] ADS-B equipment is mandatory for all aircraft flying at or above this altitude.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] ADS-B equipment is also mandatory for all IFR aircraft at any altitude.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] This applies to all Australian registered aircraft.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] Nav Canada commissioned operational use of ADS-B in 2009 and is now using it to provide coverage of its northern airspace around Hudson Bay, which previously had almost no radar coverage.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] The service was then extended to cover some oceanic areas off the east coast of Canada including the Labrador Sea, Davis Strait, Baffin Bay, and part of the North Atlantic Tracks around southern Greenland.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] The service was later extended to cover the Canadian Arctic, and to the rest of Canada.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] In 2018, Nav Canada issued an aeronautical study proposing a mandate for Aireon-compatible ADS-B Out for all aircraft in Class A Airspace by 2021 and Class B Airspace, to be completed by 2022, requiring a transponder capable of delivering antenna diversity performance.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] In response to stakeholder feedback, Nav Canada later announced that such equipment will not be mandated according to that timeline, but rather that suitably equipped aircraft would be handled on a priority basis.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] The dates upon which equipment are required for operation in Canadian airspace were announced to be 10 August 2023 for Class A Airspace, 16 May 2024 for Class B Airspace, and no sooner than 2026 for Class C, D, and E Airspace.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] By spring 2022, five ground stations were operating in Ontario, and more are currently being built, with the goal of the network covering areas with higher traffic.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] As of 2025, twelve stations operate in four provinces.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] The Canadian network is fully compatible with the United States network, and aircraft can use the same UAT (ADS-B In) receivers in both countries and the provided services operate seamlessly when crossing the border.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] An American company ADS-B Technologies created one of the largest and most successful ADS-B systems in the world (an eight-station, 350+ aircraft network that spans more than 1,200 NM across Central China).
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] This was also the first UAT installation outside the United States.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] As of March 2009, more than 1.2 million incident/failure-free flight hours had been flown with these ADS-B systems.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] In 2024, the Ministry of State Security accused that ADS-B receivers deployed by foreign organizations constitute a national security risk.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] Authorities had mounted clampdowns on enthusiasts who installed ADS-B receivers.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] As of 2010, Isavia is in the process of installing ADS-B across the North Atlantic Ocean.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] The system is made up by 18 ADS-B receiver stations in Iceland, Faroe Islands, and Greenland.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] The Airports Authority of India (AAI), which manages the country's airspace, first commissioned German company Comsoft to install ADS-B ground stations at 14 airport sites nationwide in 2012.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] Comsoft finished installing seven new ADS-B ground stations under a second phase of deployment which India subsequently integrated into its ATC system in 2014, thus completing its ground network for automatic dependent surveillance-broadcast (ADS-B) tracking of aircraft.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] The network covers the Indian subcontinent, plus parts of the Bay of Bengal and the Arabian Sea.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] LFV Group in Sweden has implemented a nationwide ADS-B network with 12 ground stations.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] Installation commenced during the spring of 2006, and the network was fully (technically) operational in 2007.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] An ADS-B–supported system was opened in Spring 2009, and is currently operational in Kiruna, Sweden.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] Based on the VDL Mode 4 standards, the network of ground stations can support services for ADS-B, TIS-B, FIS-B, GNS-B (DGNSS augmentation) and point-to-point communication, allowing aircraft equipped with VDL 4-compliant transceivers to lower fuel consumption and reduce flight times.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] United Arab Emirates commissioned three operational redundant ADS-B ground stations in early 2009 and is now using ADS-B to provide enhanced coverage of its upper airspace in combination and integrated with conventional surveillance radars.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] To reduce congestion and cope with growing aircraft traffic, the Federal Aviation Administration has been developing the Next-Generation Air Transportation System (NextGen), including ADS-B.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] ADS-B equipment is built to meet one of two sets of industry standards, DO-260B and DO-282B.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] Aircraft operating in the United States in the airspace classes listed below are required to carry equipment that produces an ADS-B Out broadcast.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] ADS-B Out broadcasts information about an aircraft through an onboard transmitter to a ground receiver, moving air traffic control from a radar-based system to a satellite-derived aircraft location system.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] There is no such mandate for ADS-B In, which receives data and provides it to in-cockpit displays.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] The FAA airspace requirements intentionally exclude some airspace that is frequently used by general aviation.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] The US Drug Enforcement Agency's aircraft and (other airborne US government surveillance) use the ADS-B method to identify in air while conducting operations.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] Operators can choose the 1090 megahertz extended squitter broadcast link, or the universal access transceiver broadcast link.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] FAA did not adopt higher performance standards that would enable all of the initial ADS-B In applications, but these can optionally be adopted.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] Fleet: 250,000 GA aircraft that will need ADS-B by 2020 of which 165,000 aircraft are subject to ADS-B Out (Class I and Class II aircraft that generally fly below 18 000 feet).
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] FAA forecasts an increase in the GA fleet from 224,172 aircraft in 2010 to 270,920 aircraft in 2031, growing an average of 0.9% per year.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] In April 2011, US federal legislation via House Bill for FAA reauthorization permits an "equipping fund" that includes a portion for some general aviation aircraft.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] The fund would provide financing at competitive rates backed by loan guarantees.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] A public-private partnership has been formed as the NextGen Equipage Fund, LLC which is managed by NEXA Capital Partners, LLC.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] The Federal Aviation Administration ADS-B implementation was broken into three segments each with a corresponding timeline.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] Ground segment implementation and deployment began in 2009 and was completed by 2013.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] Airborne equipment is user-driven and is expected to be completed both voluntarily based on perceived benefits and through regulatory actions (Rulemaking) by the FAA.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] The cost to equip with ADS-B Out capability is relatively small and would benefit the airspace with surveillance in areas not currently served by radar.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] The FAA intends to provide similar service within the NAS to what radar is currently providing (5 nmi en route and 3 nmi terminal radar standards) as a first step to implementation.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] However, ADS-B In capability is viewed as the most likely way to improve NAS throughput and enhance capacity.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] In December 2008, Acting FAA Administrator Robert A.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] Sturgell gave the go-ahead for ADS-B to go live in southern Florida.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] The south Florida installation, which consists of 11 ground stations and supporting equipment, is the first commissioned in the United States, although developmental systems have been online in Alaska, Arizona, and along the East Coast since 2004.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] The completed system will consist of 794 ground station transceivers.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] The December 2008 action is in compliance with a late-term executive order from George W.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] Bush which mandated accelerated approval of NextGen.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] ADS-B deployment and voluntary equipment, along with rule-making activities.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] Pockets of development will exploit equipment deployment in the areas that will provide proof of concept for integration to ATC automation systems deployed in the NAS.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] It is being developed at the FAA's William J.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] Hughes Technical Center near Egg Harbor City, New Jersey.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] ADS-B ground stations will be deployed throughout the NAS, with an in-service decision due in the 2012–2013 time frame.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] Completed deployment will occur in 2013–14.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] ADS-B In equipment will be based on user-perceived benefit but is expected to be providing increased situational awareness and efficiency benefits within this segment.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] Those aircraft that choose to equip in advance of any mandate will see benefits associated with preferential routes and specific applications.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] Limited radar decommissioning will begin in the time frame with an ultimate goal of a 50% reduction in the secondary surveillance radar infrastructure.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] On 27 May 2010, the FAA published its final rule mandating that by 2020 all aircraft owners will be required to have ADS-B Out capabilities when operating in any airspace that currently requires a transponder (airspace classes A, B, and C, and airspace class E at certain altitudes).
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] On 14 June 2012, FreeFlight Systems and Chevron received STC for the first rule-compliant ADS-B installation in GOMEX helicopters that was awarded by the FAA.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] They operate at their hub airports largely at night.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] Much of the benefit to these carriers is envisioned through merging and spacing the arriving and departing traffic to a more manageable flow.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] (RNAV) descent profiles, combined with CDTI, may allow crews to eventually aid controllers with assisted visual acquisition of traffic and limited cockpit-based separation of aircraft.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] The benefits to the carrier are fuel and time efficiencies associated with idle descent and shorter traffic patterns than typical radar vectoring allows.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] ERAU has equipped its training aircraft at its two main campuses in Florida and Arizona with UAT ADS-B capability as a situational safety enhancement.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] The university has been doing this since May 2003, making it the first use in general aviation.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] flight instrument system to their fleet in 2006, ERAU became the first fleet to combine a glass cockpit with ADS-B.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] UND has received an FAA grant to test ADS-B and has begun to outfit their Piper Warrior fleet with an ADS-B package.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] A concern for any ADS-B protocol is the capacity for carrying ADS-B messages from aircraft, as well as allowing the radio channel to continue to support any legacy services.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] For 1090 ES, each ADS-B message is composed of a pair of data packets.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] The greater the number of packets transmitted from one aircraft, the fewer aircraft that can participate in the system, due to the fixed and limited channel data bandwidth.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] System capacity is defined by establishing a criterion for what the worst environment is likely to be, then making that a minimum requirement for system capacity.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] For 1090 ES, both TCAS and ATCRBS/MSSR are existing users of the channel.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] 1090 ES ADS-B must not reduce the capacity of these existing systems.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] The FAA national program office and other international aviation regulators are addressing concerns about ADS-B non-secure nature of ADS-B transmissions.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] ADS-B messages can be used to know the location of an aircraft, and there is no means to guarantee that this information is not used inappropriately.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] Additionally, there are some concerns about the integrity of ADS-B transmissions.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] ADS-B messages can be produced, with simple, low-cost measures, which spoof the locations of multiple phantom aircraft to disrupt safe air travel.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] There is no foolproof means to guarantee integrity, but there are means to monitor this type of activity.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] This problem is however similar to the usage of ATCRBS/MSSR where false signals also are potentially dangerous (uncorrelated secondary tracks).
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] There are some concerns about ADS-B dependence on satellite navigation systems to generate state vector information.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] There are some general aviation concerns that ADS-B removes anonymity of the VFR aircraft operations.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] The ICAO 24-bit transponder code specifically assigned to each aircraft will allow monitoring of that aircraft when within the service volumes of the Mode-S/ADS-B system.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] Unlike the Mode A/C transponders, there is no code "1200"/"7000", which offers casual anonymity.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] Mode-S/ADS-B identifies the aircraft uniquely among all in the world, in a similar fashion as a MAC address for a network interface controller or the International Mobile Equipment Identity (IMEI) of a GSM phone.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] However, the FAA is allowing UAT-equipped aircraft to utilize a random self-assigned temporary ICAO address in conjunction with the use of beacon code 1200.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] 1090 ES-equipped aircraft using ADS-B will not have this option.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] In order for the ADS-B system to function to the fullest extent, equipment for all aircraft in the airspace is required.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] This demands that transponder technology be scalable from the smallest aircraft to the largest aircraft to allow for 100% equipage for any given airspace.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] Current transponder technology is capable of equipping larger, traditional aircraft but a new type of transponder is required for equipping aircraft that are smaller and lighter or don't have electrical systems like the large traditionally transponder-equipped aircraft.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] The requirements for these smaller and lighter aircraft are mainly size, weight, and power (SWAP) and transponder technology must allow for equipage of these types of aircraft to enable saturation of ADS-B for total visibility in any given airspace.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] On 7 June 2002 the FAA published a historical overview of its decision on the ADS-B link architecture for use in the National Airspace System (NAS).
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] A significant step forward for ADS-B is the reception by artificial satellites of the ADS-B signal.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] It was tested for the first time in 2013 on ESA's PROBA-V and it is being deployed by companies like Spire Global using low-cost nanosatellites.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] Aireon is also working on space-based ADS-B with the Iridium satellite network, a LEO (Low Earth Orbit) satellite network that was originally created to deliver phone and data service anywhere on the planet.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] The system only receives ADS-B on aircraft broadcasting on the 1090 MHz frequency.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] This limits the system generally to airliners and business aircraft, despite the fact that small aircraft are frequently off the radar due to mountains blocking the signal at low altitudes.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] The system could be compromised by smaller, private aircraft with exclusive belly-mounted ADS-B antennas, due to the aircraft fuselage blocking the signal.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] In December 2016, Flightradar24 entered an agreement with Gomspace for space-based tracking in 2016.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] SpaceX subsequently placed 66 operational and 9 spare Iridium satellites in orbit over the course of 8 launches between 14 January 2017 and 11 January 2019.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] Another 6 spare satellites remain on the ground.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] The ICAO describes space-based ADS-B as a technology equalizer, offering developing nations an airspace surveillance capability.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] By 2020, 34 nations will deploy the system, including the 17 members of the Asecna in Africa, and the Cocesna air navigation services agency in Central America.
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] More frequent updates in the North Atlantic Tracks allowed reducing longitudinal separation from 40 to 14 nmi (74 to 26 km) and lateral separations from 23 to 19 nmi (43 to 35 km).
[src:aircraft-navigation/automatic-dependent-surveillance-broadcast] The FAA plans an evaluation in the Caribbean airspace from March 2020 until 2021, to complement the unreliable Grand Turk Island radar which allows reducing separation from 30 to 5 nmi (55.6 to 9.3 km).
[src:aircraft-navigation/distance-measuring-equipment] In aviation, **distance measuring equipment** (**DME**) is a radio navigation technology that measures the slant range (distance) between an aircraft and a ground station by timing the propagation delay of radio signals in the frequency band between 960 and 1215 megahertz (MHz).
[src:aircraft-navigation/distance-measuring-equipment] Line-of-sight between the aircraft and ground station is required.
[src:aircraft-navigation/distance-measuring-equipment] An interrogator (airborne) initiates an exchange by transmitting a pulse pair, on an assigned 'channel', to the transponder ground station.
[src:aircraft-navigation/distance-measuring-equipment] The channel assignment specifies the carrier frequency and the spacing between the pulses.
[src:aircraft-navigation/distance-measuring-equipment] After a known delay, the transponder replies by transmitting a pulse pair on a frequency that is offset from the interrogation frequency by 63 MHz and having specified separation.
[src:aircraft-navigation/distance-measuring-equipment] DME systems are used worldwide, using standards set by the International Civil Aviation Organization (ICAO), RTCA, the European Union Aviation Safety Agency (EASA) and other bodies.
[src:aircraft-navigation/distance-measuring-equipment] Some countries require that aircraft operating under instrument flight rules (IFR) be equipped with a DME interrogator; in others, a DME interrogator is only required for conducting certain operations.
[src:aircraft-navigation/distance-measuring-equipment] While stand-alone DME transponders are permitted, DME transponders are usually paired with an azimuth guidance system to provide aircraft with a two-dimensional navigation capability.
[src:aircraft-navigation/distance-measuring-equipment] A common combination is a DME co-located with a VHF omnidirectional range (VOR) transmitter in a single ground station, designated as VOR/DME.
[src:aircraft-navigation/distance-measuring-equipment] When this occurs, the frequencies of the VOR and DME equipment are paired.
[src:aircraft-navigation/distance-measuring-equipment] Such a configuration enables an aircraft to determine its azimuth angle and distance from the station, a rough 2D locationing capability.
[src:aircraft-navigation/distance-measuring-equipment] DME is compatible with the distance measuring component of TACAN, the military equivalent of VOR/DME with more accurate rangefinding.
[src:aircraft-navigation/distance-measuring-equipment] A VORTAC (VOR with TACAM) installation allows both military and civil aircraft access to 2D positioning.
[src:aircraft-navigation/distance-measuring-equipment] Low-power DME transponders are also associated with some instrument landing system (ILS), ILS localizer and microwave landing system (MLS) installations.
[src:aircraft-navigation/distance-measuring-equipment] In those situations, the DME transponder frequency/pulse spacing is also paired with the ILS, LOC or MLS frequency.
[src:aircraft-navigation/distance-measuring-equipment] ICAO characterizes DME transmissions as ultra high frequency (UHF).
[src:aircraft-navigation/distance-measuring-equipment] DME is similar in principle to secondary radar ranging function, except the roles of the equipment in the aircraft and on the ground are reversed.
[src:aircraft-navigation/distance-measuring-equipment] DME was a post-war development based on the identification friend or foe (IFF) systems of World War II.
[src:aircraft-navigation/distance-measuring-equipment] Developed in Australia, DME was invented by James "Gerry" Gerrand.
[src:aircraft-navigation/distance-measuring-equipment] In 1945, after Edward George Bowen became Chief of the Division of Radiophysics at CSIRO, Brian Cooper developed DME.
[src:aircraft-navigation/distance-measuring-equipment] Based upon the Rebecca/Eureka transponding radar, the 200 MHz system weighed less, and used a dial instead of a screen.
[src:aircraft-navigation/distance-measuring-equipment] In 1946, the Provisional International Civil Aviation Organization adopted the VOR and DME airways model.
[src:aircraft-navigation/distance-measuring-equipment] In 1947, the system was deployed on commercial aircraft, and by 1953, all commercial aircraft in Australia were so equipped.
[src:aircraft-navigation/distance-measuring-equipment] In its first iteration, a DME-equipped airplane used the equipment to determine and display its distance from a land-based transponder by sending and receiving pulse pairs.
[src:aircraft-navigation/distance-measuring-equipment] The ground stations are typically co-located with VORs or VORTACs.
[src:aircraft-navigation/distance-measuring-equipment] A low-power (100 W) DME can be co-located with an ILS or MLS, where it provides an accurate distance to touchdown, similar to that otherwise provided by ILS marker beacons.
[src:aircraft-navigation/distance-measuring-equipment] A newer role for DMEs is DME/DME area navigation (RNAV).
[src:aircraft-navigation/distance-measuring-equipment] Owing to the generally superior accuracy of DME relative to VOR, navigation using two DMEs (using trilateration/distance) permits operations that navigating with VOR/DME (using azimuth/distance) does not.
[src:aircraft-navigation/distance-measuring-equipment] However, it requires that the aircraft have RNAV capabilities, and some operations also require an inertial reference unit.
[src:aircraft-navigation/distance-measuring-equipment] A typical DME ground transponder for en-route or terminal navigation will have a 1 kW peak pulse output on the assigned UHF channel.
[src:aircraft-navigation/distance-measuring-equipment] The DME system comprises a UHF (L-band) transmitter/receiver (interrogator) in the aircraft and a UHF (L-band) receiver/transmitter (transponder) on the ground.
[src:aircraft-navigation/distance-measuring-equipment] 150 interrogation pulse-pairs per second.
[src:aircraft-navigation/distance-measuring-equipment] The aircraft interrogates the ground transponder with a series of pulse-pairs (interrogations) and, after a precise time delay (typically 50 µs), the ground station replies with an identical sequence of pulse-pairs.
[src:aircraft-navigation/distance-measuring-equipment] The DME receiver in the aircraft searches for reply pulse-pairs (X-mode = 12 µs spacing) that match its original interrogation pattern.
[src:aircraft-navigation/distance-measuring-equipment] (Pulse-pairs that are not coincident with the individual aircraft's interrogation pattern, e.g. not synchronous, are referred to as filler pulse-pairs, or squitter.
[src:aircraft-navigation/distance-measuring-equipment] Less than 30 interrogation pulse-pairs per second, as the average number of pulses in SEARCH and TRACK is limited to max 30 pulse pairs per second.
[src:aircraft-navigation/distance-measuring-equipment] The aircraft interrogator locks on to the DME ground station once it recognizes a particular reply pulse sequence that has the same spacing as the original interrogation sequence.
[src:aircraft-navigation/distance-measuring-equipment] Once the receiver is locked on, it has a narrower window in which to look for the echoes and can retain lock.
[src:aircraft-navigation/distance-measuring-equipment] A radio signal takes approximately 12.36 µs to travel 1 nautical mile (1,852 m) to the target and back.
[src:aircraft-navigation/distance-measuring-equipment] The distance formula, *distance = speed × time*, is used by the DME receiver to calculate its distance from the DME ground station.
[src:aircraft-navigation/distance-measuring-equipment] The speed in the calculation is the propagation speed of the radio pulse, which is the speed of light (roughly 300,000,000 m/s or 162,000 nmi/s).
[src:aircraft-navigation/distance-measuring-equipment] The time in the calculation is ½(*total time* − *reply delay*), hence the distance is *c* × ½(*total time* − *reply delay*), where *c* is the speed of light.
[src:aircraft-navigation/distance-measuring-equipment] The accuracy of DME ground stations is 185 m (±0.1 nmi).
[src:aircraft-navigation/distance-measuring-equipment] It's important to understand that DME provides the physical distance between the aircraft antenna and the DME transponder antenna.
[src:aircraft-navigation/distance-measuring-equipment] This distance is often referred to as 'slant range' and depends trigonometrically upon the aircraft altitude above the transponder as well as the ground distance between them.
[src:aircraft-navigation/distance-measuring-equipment] For example, an aircraft directly above the DME station at 6,076 ft (1 nmi) altitude would still show 1.0 nmi (1.9 km) on the DME readout.
[src:aircraft-navigation/distance-measuring-equipment] The aircraft is technically a mile away, just a mile straight up.
[src:aircraft-navigation/distance-measuring-equipment] Slant range error is most pronounced at high altitudes when close to the DME station.
[src:aircraft-navigation/distance-measuring-equipment] Radio-navigation aids must keep a certain degree of accuracy, given by international standards, FAA, EASA, ICAO, etc.
[src:aircraft-navigation/distance-measuring-equipment] To assure this is the case, flight inspection organizations check periodically critical parameters with properly equipped aircraft to calibrate and certify DME precision.
[src:aircraft-navigation/distance-measuring-equipment] ICAO recommends that the error be no larger than (0.25 nmi + 1.25% × actual distance).
[src:aircraft-navigation/distance-measuring-equipment] A typical DME ground-based transponder beacon has a limit of 2700 interrogations per second (pulse pairs per second – pps).
[src:aircraft-navigation/distance-measuring-equipment] Thus it can provide distance information for up to 100 aircraft at a time—95% of transmissions for aircraft in tracking mode (typically 25 pps) and 5% in search mode (typically 150 pps).
[src:aircraft-navigation/distance-measuring-equipment] Above this limit the transponder avoids overload by limiting the sensitivity (gain) of the receiver.
[src:aircraft-navigation/distance-measuring-equipment] Replies to weaker (normally the more distant) interrogations are ignored to lower the transponder load.
[src:aircraft-navigation/distance-measuring-equipment] DME frequencies are paired to VOR frequencies and a DME interrogator is designed to automatically tune to the corresponding DME frequency when the associated VOR frequency is selected.
[src:aircraft-navigation/distance-measuring-equipment] An airplane's DME interrogator uses frequencies from 1025 to 1150 MHz.
[src:aircraft-navigation/distance-measuring-equipment] DME transponders transmit on a channel in the 962 to 1213 MHz range and receive on a corresponding channel between 1025 and 1150 MHz.
[src:aircraft-navigation/distance-measuring-equipment] The band is divided into 126 channels for interrogation and 126 channels for reply.
[src:aircraft-navigation/distance-measuring-equipment] The interrogation and reply frequencies always differ by 63 MHz.
[src:aircraft-navigation/distance-measuring-equipment] The spacing and bandwidth of each channel is 1 MHz and a bandwidth of 1MHz.
[src:aircraft-navigation/distance-measuring-equipment] Technical references to X and Y channels relate only to the spacing of the individual pulses in the DME pulse pair: 12 µs spacing for X channels and 30 µs spacing for Y channels.
[src:aircraft-navigation/distance-measuring-equipment] DME facilities identify themselves with a 1,350 Hz Morse code three-letter identity.
[src:aircraft-navigation/distance-measuring-equipment] If co-located with a VOR or ILS, it will have the same identity code as the parent facility.
[src:aircraft-navigation/distance-measuring-equipment] Additionally, the DME will identify itself between those of the parent facility.
[src:aircraft-navigation/distance-measuring-equipment] The DME identity is 1,350 Hz to differentiate itself from the 1,020 Hz tone of the VOR or the ILS localizer.
[src:aircraft-navigation/distance-measuring-equipment] However, many have operational restrictions largely based on line-of-sight blockage, and actual performance may be different.
[src:aircraft-navigation/distance-measuring-equipment] Aeronautical Information Manual states, presumably referring to high altitude DME transponders: "reliable signals may be received at distances up to 199 nautical miles [369 km] at line-of-sight altitude".
[src:aircraft-navigation/distance-measuring-equipment] DME transponders associated with an ILS or other instrument approach are intended for use during an approach to a particular runway, either one or both ends.
[src:aircraft-navigation/distance-measuring-equipment] They are not authorized for general navigation; neither a minimum range nor height is specified.
[src:aircraft-navigation/distance-measuring-equipment] DME frequency usage, channelization and pairing with other navaids (VOR, ILS, etc.) are defined by ICAO.
[src:aircraft-navigation/distance-measuring-equipment] 252 DME *channels* are defined by the combination of their interrogation frequency, interrogation pulse spacing, reply frequency, and reply pulse spacing.
[src:aircraft-navigation/distance-measuring-equipment] These channels are labeled 1X, 1Y, 2X, 2Y, ...
[src:aircraft-navigation/distance-measuring-equipment] X channels (which came first) have both interrogation and reply pulse pairs spaced by 12 µs.
[src:aircraft-navigation/distance-measuring-equipment] Y channels (which were added to increase capacity) have interrogation pulse pairs spaced by 36 µs and reply pulse pairs spaced by 30 µs.
[src:aircraft-navigation/distance-measuring-equipment] A total of 252 frequencies are defined (but not all used) for DME interrogations and replies—specifically, 962, 963, ...
[src:aircraft-navigation/distance-measuring-equipment] 1150 MHz (126 total), and are the same for X and Y channels.
[src:aircraft-navigation/distance-measuring-equipment] For a given channel, the reply frequency is 63 MHz below or above the interrogation frequency.
[src:aircraft-navigation/distance-measuring-equipment] The reply frequency is different for X and Y channels, and different for channels numbered 1–63 and 64–126.
[src:aircraft-navigation/distance-measuring-equipment] Not all defined channels/frequencies are assigned.
[src:aircraft-navigation/distance-measuring-equipment] There are assignment 'holes' centered on 1030 and 1090 MHz to provide protection for the secondary surveillance radar (SSR) system.
[src:aircraft-navigation/distance-measuring-equipment] In many countries, there is also an assignment 'hole' centered on 1176.45 MHz to protect the GPS L5 frequency.
[src:aircraft-navigation/distance-measuring-equipment] These three 'holes' remove approximately 60 MHz from the frequencies available for use.
[src:aircraft-navigation/distance-measuring-equipment] Precision DME (DME/P), a component of the Microwave Landing System, is assigned to Z channels, which have a third set of interrogation and reply pulse spacings.
[src:aircraft-navigation/distance-measuring-equipment] The Z channels are multiplexed with the Y channels and do not materially affect the channel plan.
[src:aircraft-navigation/distance-measuring-equipment] In 2020 one company presented its 'Fifth-Generation DME'.
[src:aircraft-navigation/distance-measuring-equipment] Although compatible with existing equipment, this iteration provides greater accuracy (down to 5 meters using DME/DME trilateration), with a further reduction to 3 meters using a further refinement.
[src:aircraft-navigation/distance-measuring-equipment] The 3-meter equipment is being considered as part of Europe's SESAR project, with possible deployment by 2023.
[src:aircraft-navigation/distance-measuring-equipment] In the twenty-first century, aerial navigation has become increasingly reliant on satellite guidance.
[src:aircraft-navigation/distance-measuring-equipment] One advantage of the fifth-generation equipment proposed in 2020 is its ability to be function-checked by drone flights, which will significantly reduce the expense and delays of previous crewed certification flight tests.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] In aviation, the **instrument landing system** (**ILS**) is a precision radio navigation system that provides short-range guidance to aircraft to allow them to approach a runway at night or in bad weather.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] In its original form, it allows a pilot, through a cockpit mounted instrument in the aircraft that displays lateral and vertical guidance indications (needles),, to approach until the aircraft is 200 feet (61 m) over the ground, within 1⁄2 mile (800 m) of the runway.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] At that point the runway should be visible to the pilot; if it is not, they perform a missed approach.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] Bringing the aircraft this close to the runway dramatically increases the range of weather conditions in which a safe landing can be made.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] Other versions of the system, or "categories", have further reduced the minimum altitudes, runway visual ranges (RVRs), and transmitter and monitoring configurations designed depending on the normal expected weather patterns and airport safety requirements.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] ILS uses two directional radio signals, the *localizer* (108 to 112 MHz frequency), which provides horizontal guidance, and the *glideslope* (329.15 to 335 MHz frequency) for vertical guidance.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] The relationship between the aircraft's position and these signals is displayed on an aircraft instrument, often as additional pointers in the attitude indicator.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] The pilot attempts to maneuver the aircraft to keep the indicators centered while they approach the runway to the decision height.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] Optional *marker beacon(s)* provide distance information as the approach proceeds, including the *middle marker* (MM), placed close to the position of the (CAT 1) decision height.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] Markers are largely being phased out and replaced by distance measuring equipment (DME).
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] To aid the transition from instrument landing to visual, lighting on the runway is often extended towards the decision point using a series of high-intensity lights known as the approach lighting system.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] A number of radio-based landing systems were developed between the 1920s and 1940s, notably the Lorenz beam, which was a blind-landing radio navigation system developed by C.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] Lorenz AG for bad weather landing, which saw relatively wide use in Europe and was also installed on a number of airports on other continents worldwide prior to World War II.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] Later also the patent for adding vertical guidance like in today's ILS was awarded.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] The US-developed SCS-51 system provided a better accuracy for vertical and horizontal guidance.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] Many sets were installed at airbases in the United Kingdom during World War II.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] After the formation of the International Civil Aviation Organization (ICAO) in 1947, ILS was selected as the first international standard precision approach system and was published in ICAO Annex 10 in 1950.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] Further development enabled ILS systems to provide up to CAT-III approaches.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] The Precision approach radar (PAR) radar-based ground-controlled approach (GCA), provides the pilot with the necessary horizontal and vertical guidance via VHF- or UHF-voice-communication link.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] The ATC-controller “talks the pilot down” with the PAR derived guidance information displayed on a special Plan position indicator (PPI) via VHF- or UHF-voice-communication.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] PAR GCA requires no equipment in the aircraft other than the VHF- or UHF-communication equipment, but requires the pilot and controller to be certified for this use.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] The second ICAO standard system for precision approach up to CAT-III is the microwave landing system (MLS) which was also planned for implementation by NATO to replace PAR.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] Due to the foreseen availability of cost-free GPS service for civil use and later the promise of DGPS, to provide additional correctional data via a VHF-Data-Link to improve reliability up to CAT-I level, most states opted to delay, until today, the implementation of MLS.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] In addition to the cost for the ground-based MLS system, aircraft operators were forced to equip aircraft, in addition to the MLS-receiver, with a C-Band antenna.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] The retrofit of a C-Band antenna in the aircraft's fuselage is more time consuming and costly than just retrofitting an MLS-receiver.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] However more than thousand fixed and transportable MLS systems have been deployed, e.g. in Europe, and more than thousand civil and military aircraft were equipped with MLS equipment and antenna and in use for about a decade.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] While the promised availability of free access to GPS signals and later additional global navigation satellite systems (GNSSs) for precision approaches reducing the need for the airport infrastructure compared to a single ILS-system (ILS-LLZ, GP and associated Monitors) looked promising.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] Ensuring safe 24/7 operation identical to ILS with the same continuity of service, under all operational weather conditions, aircraft orientation during all phases of a flight proved to be impossible without an additional augmentation VHF-Data-Link.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] One reason is the weak satellite based signals, which unlike much stronger ILS- or MLS- signals, very sensitive even to very weak RFI-, intentional Jamming- or Spoofing signals.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] The DGPS system was, after further development and modifications, standardized by ICAO as GBAS ground-based augmentation system, in the US known as Local-Area Augmentation System (LAAS).
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] Today GBAS is the third ICAO standard system for precision landing capable of up to CAT-III.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] Work on standards to support multi-constellation, which means adding support for the now available Galileo, GLONASS and BeiDou GNSS system is ongoing.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] Like for MLS aircraft require for GBAS a receiver for the GBAS datalink and a horizontally polarized VHF-antenna.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] While IFR certified civil aircraft are already all equipped with horizontally polarized VHF antennas for ILS- and VOR-reception, some military aircraft only have vertically polarized VHF antennas for VHF voice communication (e.g.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] While ICAO also standardized the use of the additional vertical polarization, so far no vertically polarized GBAS installation have been published to be available.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] Similar to the MLS until today compared to ILS-installations that are in use worldwide, only a limited number of GBAS systems have been deployed and are still in use currently.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] Today in Europe mostly serve only a single or parallel runways, e.g.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] By 2015, the number of US airports supporting ILS-like LPV approaches exceeded the number of ILS installations, and this may lead to the eventual removal of ILS at most airports.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] ILS therefore remains the only available precision approach systems supported by all IFR equipped civil aircraft.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] Previous blind landing radio aids typically took the form of *beam* systems of various types.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] These normally consisted of a radio transmitter that was connected to a motorized switch to produce a pattern of Morse code dots and dashes.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] The switch also controlled which of two directional antennae the signal was sent to.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] The resulting signal sent into the air consists of dots sent to one side of the runway and dashes to the other.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] The beams were wide enough so they overlapped in the center.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] To use the system an aircraft only needed a conventional radio receiver.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] As they approached the airport they would tune in the signal and listen to it in their headphones.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] They would hear dots and dashes (Morse code "A" or "N"), if they were to the side of the runway, or if they were properly aligned, the two mixed together to produce a steady tone, the *equisignal*.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] The accuracy of this measurement was highly dependent on the skill of the operator, who listened to the signal on earphones in a noisy aircraft, often while communicating with the tower.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] Accuracy of the system was normally on the order of 3 degrees in azimuth.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] Nevertheless, the final decision to land was made at only 300 metres (980 ft) from the airport.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] The ILS, developed just prior to the start of World War II, used a more complex system of signals and an antenna array to achieve higher accuracy.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] This requires significantly more complexity in the ground station and transmitters, with the advantage that the signals can be accurately decoded in the aircraft using simple electronics and displayed directly on analog instruments.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] The instruments can be placed in front of the pilot, eliminating the need for a radio operator to continually monitor the signals and relay the results to the pilot over the intercom.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] Key to its operation is a concept known as the amplitude modulation index, a measure of how strongly the amplitude modulation is applied to the carrier frequency.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] In the earlier beam systems, the signal was turned on and off entirely, corresponding to a modulation index of 100%.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] The determination of angle within the beam is based on the comparison of the audible strength of the two signals.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] In ILS, a more complex system of signals and antennas varies the modulation of two signals across the entire width of the beam pattern.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] The system relies on the use of sidebands, secondary frequencies that are created when two different signals are mixed.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] For instance, if one takes a radio frequency signal at 10 MHz and mixes that with an audible tone at 2500 Hz, four signals will be produced, at the original signals' frequencies of 2500 and 10000000 Hz, and sidebands 9997500 and 10002500 Hz.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] The original 2500 Hz signal's frequency is too low to travel far from an antenna, but the other three signals are all radio frequency and can be effectively transmitted.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] ILS starts by mixing two modulating signals to the carrier, one at 90 Hz and another at 150.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] This creates a signal with five radio frequencies in total, the carrier and four sidebands.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] This combined signal, known as the CSB for "carrier and sidebands", is sent out evenly from an antenna array.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] The CSB is also sent into a circuit that suppresses the original carrier, leaving only the four sideband signals.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] This signal, known as SBO for "sidebands only", is also sent to the antenna array.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] For lateral guidance, known as the *localizer*, the antenna is normally placed centrally at the far end of the runway and consists of multiple antennas in an array normally about the width of the runway.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] Each individual antenna has a particular phase shift and power level applied only to the SBO signal such that the resulting signal is retarded 90 degrees on the left side of the runway and advanced 90 degrees on the right.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] Additionally, the 150 Hz signal is inverted on one side of the pattern, another 180 degree shift.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] Due to the way the signals mix in space the SBO signals destructively interfere with and almost eliminate each other along the centerline, leaving the CSB signal predominating.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] At any other location, on either side of the centerline, the SBO and CSB signals combine in different ways so that one modulating signal predominates.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] A receiver in front of the array will receive both of these signals mixed together.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] Using simple electronic filters, the original carrier and two sidebands can be separated and demodulated to extract the original amplitude-modulated 90 and 150 Hz signals.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] These are then averaged to produce two direct current (DC) signals.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] Each of these signals represents not the strength of the original signal, but the strength of the modulation relative to the carrier, which varies across the beam pattern.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] This has the great advantage that the measurement of angle is independent of range.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] The two DC signals are then sent to a conventional voltmeter, with the 90 Hz output pulling the needle right and the other left.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] Along the centreline the two modulating tones of the sidebands will be cancelled out and both voltages will be zero, leaving the needle centered in the display.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] If the aircraft is far to the left, the 90 Hz signal will produce a strong DC voltage (predominates), and the 150 Hz signal is minimised, pulling the needle all the way to the right.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] This means the voltmeter directly displays both the direction and magnitude of the turn needed to bring the aircraft back to the runway centreline.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] As the measurement compares different parts of a single signal entirely in electronics, it provides angular resolution of less than a degree, and allows the construction of a precision approach.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] Although the encoding scheme is complex, and requires a considerable amount of ground equipment, the resulting signal is both far more accurate than the older beam-based systems and is far more resistant to common forms of interference.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] For instance, static in the signal will affect both sub-signals equally, so it will have no effect on the result.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] Similarly, changes in overall signal strength as the aircraft approaches the runway, or changes due to fading, will have little effect on the resulting measurement because they would normally affect both channels equally.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] The system is subject to multipath distortion effects due to the use of multiple frequencies, but because those effects are dependent on the terrain, they are generally fixed in location and can be accounted for through adjustments in the antenna or phase shifters.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] Additionally, because it is the encoding of the signal within the beam that contains the angle information, not the strength of the beam, the signal does not have to be tightly focussed in space.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] In the older beam systems, the accuracy of the equisignal area was a function of the pattern of the two directional signals, which demanded that they be relatively narrow.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] ILS installations are normally required to be usable within 10 degrees on either side of the runway centerline at 25 nautical miles (46 km; 29 mi), and 35 degrees on either side at 17 nautical miles (31 km; 20 mi).
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] This allows for a wide variety of approach paths.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] The *glideslope* works in the same general fashion as the localizer and uses the same encoding, but is normally transmitted to produce a centerline at an angle of 3 degrees above horizontal from an antenna beside the runway instead of the end.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] The only difference between the signals is that the localizer is transmitted using lower carrier frequencies, using 40 selected channels between 108.10 MHz and 111.95 MHz, whereas the glideslope has a corresponding set of 40 channels between 328.6 and 335.4 MHz.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] The higher frequencies generally result in the glideslope radiating antennas being smaller.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] The channel pairs are not linear; localizer channel 1 is at 108.10 and paired with glideslope at 334.70, whereas channel two is 108.15 and 334.55.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] There are gaps and jumps through both bands.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] Many illustrations of the ILS concept show the system operating more similarly to beam systems with the 90 Hz signal on one side and the 150 on the other.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] These illustrations are inaccurate; both signals are radiated across the entire beam pattern, it is their relative difference in the depth of modulation (DDM) that changes dependent upon the position of the approaching aircraft.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] An instrument approach procedure chart (or 'approach plate') is published for each ILS approach to provide the information needed to fly an ILS approach during instrument flight rules (IFR) operations.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] A chart includes the radio frequencies used by the ILS components or navaids and the prescribed minimum visibility requirements.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] An aircraft approaching a runway is guided by the ILS receivers in the aircraft by performing modulation depth comparisons.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] Many aircraft can route signals into the autopilot to fly the approach automatically.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] An ILS consists of two independent sub-systems.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] The localizer provides lateral guidance; the glide slope provides vertical guidance.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] A localizer (LOC, or LLZ until ICAO standardisation) is an antenna array normally located beyond the departure end of the runway and generally consists of several pairs of directional antennas.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] The localizer will allow the aircraft to turn and match the aircraft with the runway.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] After that, the pilots will activate approach phase (APP).
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] Due to the complexity of ILS localizer and glide slope systems, there are some limitations.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] Localizer systems are sensitive to obstructions in the signal broadcast area, such as large buildings or hangars.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] Glide slope systems are also limited by the terrain in front of the glide slope antennas.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] If terrain is sloping or uneven, reflections can create an uneven glidepath, causing unwanted needle deflections.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] Additionally, since the ILS signals are pointed in one direction by the positioning of the arrays, glide slope supports only straight-line approaches with a constant angle of descent.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] Installation of an ILS can be costly because of siting criteria and the complexity of the antenna system.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] ILS critical areas and ILS sensitive areas are established to avoid hazardous reflections that would affect the radiated signal.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] The location of these critical areas can prevent aircraft from using certain taxiways leading to delays in takeoffs, increased hold times, and increased separation between aircraft.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] In addition to the previously mentioned navigational signals, the localizer provides for ILS facility identification by periodically transmitting a 1,020 Hz Morse code identification signal, that always starts with Morse Code letter "I", for ILS, two dots.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] For example, the ILS for runway 4R at John F.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] Kennedy International Airport transmits IJFK to identify itself, while runway 4L is known as IHIQ.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] This lets users know the facility is operating normally and that they are tuned to the correct ILS.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] The glide slope station transmits no identification signal, so ILS equipment relies on the localizer for identification.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] It is essential that any failure of the ILS to provide safe guidance be detected immediately by the pilot.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] To achieve this, monitors continually assess the vital characteristics of the transmissions.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] If any significant deviation beyond strict limits is detected, either the ILS is automatically switched off or the navigation and identification components are removed from the carrier.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] Either of these actions will activate an indication ('failure flag') on the instruments of an aircraft using the ILS.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] Modern localizer antennas are highly directional.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] However, usage of older, less directional antennas allows a runway to have a non-precision approach called a *localizer back course*.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] This lets aircraft land using the signal transmitted from the back of the localizer array.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] Highly directional antennas do not provide a sufficient signal to support a back course.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] In the United States, back course approaches are typically associated with Category I systems at smaller airports that do not have an ILS on both ends of the primary runway.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] Pilots flying a back course should disregard any glide slope indication.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] On some legacy installations, marker beacons operating at a carrier frequency of 75 MHz are provided.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] When the transmission from a marker beacon is received it activates an indicator on the pilot's instrument panel and the identity code and tone of the beacon is audible to the pilot.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] The distance from the runway at which this indication should be received is published in the documentation for that approach, together with the height at which the aircraft should be if correctly established on the ILS.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] This provides a check on the correct function of the glide slope.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] Instead of marker beacons, modern ILS installations use DME.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] Co-located with the ILS glidepath transmitter near the touchdown point, the DME provides a display of aircraft distance to the runway.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] Distance measuring equipment (DME) provides pilots with a slant range measurement of distance to the runway.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] DMEs are augmenting or replacing markers in many installations.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] The DME provides more accurate and continuous monitoring of correct progress on the ILS glide slope to the pilot, and does not require an installation outside the airport boundary.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] When used in conjunction with a dual runway approach ILS, the DME is often sited midway between the reciprocal runway thresholds with the internal delay modified so that one unit can provide distance information to either runway threshold.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] For approaches where a DME is specified in lieu of marker beacons, *DME required* is noted on the instrument approach procedure and the aircraft must have at least one operating DME unit, or an IFR-approved system using a GNSS (an RNAV system meeting TSO-C129/ -C145/-C146), to begin the approach.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] Compass locators are low-powered (less than 25 W) non-directional beacons and are received and indicated by the automatic direction finder receiver.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] It ranges over 15 miles and operate between 190 and 535 kHz.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] When used in conjunction with an ILS front course, the compass locator facilities are collocated with the outer and/or middle marker facilities and can be used to substitute an outer marker, in which case it will transmit at 400 W.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] The coding identification of the outer locator consists of the first two letters of the three-letter identifier of the associated localizer.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] Some installations include medium- or high-intensity approach light systems (abbreviated *ALS*).
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] Most often, these are at larger airports but many small general aviation airports in the U.S. have approach lights to support their ILS installations and obtain low-visibility minimums.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] The ALS assists the pilot in transitioning from instrument to visual flight, and to align the aircraft visually with the runway centerline.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] Pilot observation of the approach lighting system at the Decision Altitude allows the pilot to continue descending towards the runway, even if the runway or runway lights cannot be seen, since the ALS counts as runway end environment.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] In the U.S., an ILS without approach lights may have CAT I ILS visibility minimums as low as 3⁄4 mile (1.2 km) (runway visual range of 4,000 feet (1,200 m)) if the required obstacle clearance surfaces are clear of obstructions.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] In effect, ALS extends the runway environment out towards the landing aircraft and allows low-visibility operations.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] CAT II and III ILS approaches generally require complex high-intensity approach light systems, while medium-intensity systems are usually paired with CAT I ILS approaches.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] At some non-towered airports, the pilot controls the lighting system; for example, the pilot can key the microphone seven times to turn on the lights on the high intensity, five times to medium intensity or three times for low intensity.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] Once established on an approach, the pilot follows the ILS approach path indicated by the localizer and descends along the glide path to the decision height.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] Usually, the decision on whether or not the pilot continues with the approach relies on whether the runway is visible or not, or if the runway is clear or not.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] 150 ft (46 m) allowed by FAA with RVR > 1,400 ft (430 m), CAT II aircraft and crew, CAT II/III HUD and CAT II/III missed approach.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] Properly equipped runways (HIAL, TDZL, CL) and/or use of FD or AP or HUD to DA.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] Airports approved for scheduled air carrier operations with less than 1,200 feet of RVR are required to have additional lighting systems.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] Not used as an aircraft would have to be towed from the runway.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] Smaller aircraft generally are equipped to fly only a CAT I ILS.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] On larger aircraft, these approaches typically are controlled by the flight control system with the flight crew providing supervision.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] CAT I relies only on altimeter indications for decision height, whereas CAT II and CAT III approaches use radio altimeter (RA) to determine decision height.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] An ILS must shut down upon internal detection of a fault condition.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] Higher categories require shorter response times; therefore, ILS equipment is required to shut down more quickly.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] For example, a CAT I localizer must shut down within 10 seconds of detecting a fault, but a CAT III localizer must shut down in less than 2 seconds.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] In contrast to other operations, CAT III weather minima do not provide sufficient visual references to allow a manual landing to be made.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] CAT IIIb minima depend on roll-out control and redundancy of the autopilot, because they give only enough time for the pilot to decide whether the aircraft will land in the touchdown zone (basically CAT IIIa) and to ensure safety during rollout (basically CAT IIIb).
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] Therefore, an automatic landing system is mandatory to perform Category III operations.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] Its reliability must be sufficient to control the aircraft to touchdown in CAT IIIa operations and through rollout to a safe taxi speed in CAT IIIb (and CAT IIIc when authorized).
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] In the United States, airports with CAT III approaches have listings for CAT IIIa and IIIb or just CAT III on the instrument approach plate (U.S.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] CAT IIIb RVR minimums are limited by the runway/taxiway lighting and support facilities, and are consistent with the airport surface movement guidance control system (SMGCS) plan.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] Operations below 600 ft RVR require taxiway centerline lights and taxiway red stop bar lights.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] If the CAT IIIb RVR minimums on a runway end are 600 feet (180 m), which is a common figure in the U.S., ILS approaches to that runway end with RVR below 600 feet (180 m) qualify as CAT IIIc and require special taxi procedures, lighting, and approval conditions to permit the landings.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] FAA Order 8400.13D limits CAT III to 300 ft RVR or better.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] Order 8400.13D (2009) allows *special authorization CAT II* approaches to runways without ALSF-2 approach lights and/or touchdown zone/centerline lights, which has expanded the number of potential CAT II runways.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] In each case, a suitably equipped aircraft and appropriately qualified crew are required.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] For example, CAT IIIb requires a fail-operational system, along with a crew who are qualified and current, while CAT I does not.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] A HUD that allows the pilot to perform aircraft maneuvers rather than an automatic system is considered as fail-operational.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] A HUD allows the flight crew to fly the aircraft using the guidance cues from the ILS sensors such that if a safe landing is in doubt, the crew can respond in an appropriate and timely manner.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] HUD is becoming increasingly popular with "feeder" airlines and most manufacturers of regional jets are now offering HUDs as either standard or optional equipment.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] A HUD can provide capability to take off in low visibility.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] Some commercial aircraft are equipped with automatic landing systems that allow the aircraft to land without transitioning from instruments to visual conditions for a normal landing.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] Such autoland operations require specialized equipment, procedures and training, and involve the aircraft, airport, and the crew.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] Autoland is the only way some major airports such as Charles de Gaulle Airport remain operational every day of the year.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] Some modern aircraft are equipped with enhanced flight vision systems based on infrared sensors, that provide a day-like visual environment and allow operations in conditions and at airports that would otherwise not be suitable for a landing.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] Commercial aircraft also frequently use such equipment for takeoffs when *takeoff minima* are not met.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] For both automatic and HUD landing systems, the equipment requires special approval for its design and also for each individual installation.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] The design takes into consideration additional safety requirements for operating an aircraft close to the ground and the ability of the flight crew to react to a system anomaly.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] The equipment also has additional maintenance requirements to ensure that it is capable of supporting reduced visibility operations.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] Nearly all of this pilot training and qualification work is done in simulators with various degrees of fidelity.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] At a controlled airport, air traffic control will direct aircraft to the localizer course via assigned headings, making sure aircraft do not get too close to each other (maintain separation), but also avoiding delay as much as possible.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] Several aircraft can be on the ILS at the same time, several miles apart.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] An aircraft that has turned onto the inbound heading and is within two and a half degrees of the localizer course (half scale deflection or less shown by the course deviation indicator) is said to be *established* on the approach.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] Typically, an aircraft is established by at least 2 nautical miles (3.7 km) prior to the final approach point (glideslope intercept at the specified altitude).
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] Aircraft deviation from the optimal path is indicated to the flight crew by means of a display dial (a carryover from when an analog meter movement indicated deviation from the course line via voltages sent from the ILS receiver).
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] The output from the ILS receiver goes to the display system (head-down display and head-up display if installed) and may go to a Flight Control Computer.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] An aircraft landing procedure can be either *coupled* where the autopilot or Flight Control Computer directly flies the aircraft and the flight crew monitor the operation, or *uncoupled* where the flight crew flies the aircraft manually to keep the localizer and glideslope indicators centered.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] Tests of the ILS began in 1929 in the United States, with Jimmy Doolittle becoming the first pilot to take off, fly and land an airplane using instruments alone, without a view outside the cockpit.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] Doolittle flew a Consolidated NY2 equipped with a Sperry artificial horizon and gyroscope, a Paul Kollsman altimeter, and a tuned reed indicator to visualize his relationship to a National Bureau of Standards localizer.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] In 1928, the NSB's Harry Diamond proposed modifying low-frequency radio range as a localizer directional beam, supplemented with two high frequency beacons aligned with the approach path, while Francis Dunmore proposed a landing beam angled up from the ground as a safe glide slope.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] The combination of localizer, marker beacons, and glide slope provided a three dimensional path to the airport.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] In 1934, United Airlines, working with Bendix Aviation, modified this NSB system with a UHF localizer, producing an approach aid.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] Though not appropriate for blind landings, it became a system for instrument low approaches to within an altitude of two hundred feet, from which a pilot could then land visually.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] Duplicated in Japan, the Soviet Union, while in 1932, Ernst Kramar developed the idea in a joint project between Lorenz, Telefunken and Deutsche Versuchsanstalt für Luftfahrt.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] This version was quickly adopted in Europe.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] Between 1931 and 1933, Albert Francis Hegenberger developed the U.S.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] WWI radio direction finders, radio compasses, were deployed on aircraft as an automatic direction finder by Geoffrey Kreusi.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] The A-1 system used two omnidirectional radio transmitters called *compass locators*, one next to the airport, and another 1.5 miles away.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] After WWII, a compass locator was added to the NSB marker beacon as an approach aid.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] Navy Office of Naval Intelligence cloned the NSB system into their YB system.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] Though unsuitable for carrier landings, the navy used it for seaplanes.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] In 1938, a commercial version of the YB system manufactured by Air-Track Corporation was used in the first passenger flight blind landing.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] A basic system, fully operative, was introduced in 1932 at Berlin-Tempelhof Central Airport (Germany) named LFF or "Lorenz beam" after its inventor, the C.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] The Civil Aeronautics Board (CAB) of the United States authorized installation of the system in 1941 at six locations.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] The first landing of a scheduled U.S. passenger airliner using ILS was on January 26, 1938, when a Pennsylvania Central Airlines Boeing 247D flew from Washington, D.C., to Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania, and landed in a snowstorm using only the Instrument Landing System.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] Yet, the NSB system, and derivatives, had several limitations, including not having a straight glide path.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] The current curved glidepath resulted in flying at an altitude of 50 feet, a half mile before entering the airport boundary.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] A straight glide path was needed to simplify the approach and ensure obstacle clearance.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] The army wanted a ten mile straight glide path.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] The current system also used the earth's surface as a reflector, which destabilized and distorted the glidepath with changing surface conditions.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] In 1938, the Bureau of Air Commerce contracted the ITT to improve the NSB system.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] In 1939, the improved system was demonstrated in Indianapolis, though it still had a 2-3 mile curved glide slope.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] In 1940, President Roosevelt approved a National Academy of Sciences recommendation allowing the Civil Aeronautics Authority to install ten ITT Indianapolis systems , while the army pursued a microwave system development project with MIT.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] With the advent of WWII in 1941, the army began deploying the CAA localizer and marker beacon systems throughout the U.S., while the AAF and CAA adopted standard approach procedures for each airport.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] In 1942, the Army Air Force (AAF) took over the CAA Indianapolis facility and began developing an army version with the help of ITT's International Telephone and Radio Manufacturing Company.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] The 110 MHz localizer and 93.7 MHz glide path were both replaced with 330 MHz electronics, which reduced environmental influences, the glidepath was made straight, and the system made portable with standard vacuum tube sets.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] In 1942, the AAF initiated testing of this SCS-51 system.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] In 1943, the system became the standard for both the army and navy, and was deployed along the North Atlantic air ferry route.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] In 1944, the SCS-51 was adopted by the Eighth Air Force, the Ninth Air Force, and the RAF, in the European theater..
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] Nations took over, and expanded, the facilities established during the war by the Air Transport Command.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] The SCS-51 was also adopted as the international standard, since the system also was available to use immediately, easy and inexpensive to manufacture, without any proprietary or military secrets.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] The first fully automatic landing by a commercial airliner using ILS occurred in March 1964 at Bedford Airport in the UK.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] The instrument landing systems market revenue was US$1,215 million in 2019, and is expected to reach US$1,667 million in 2025, with a CAGR of 5.41% during 2020–2025 even with the negative effects of the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] The advent of the Global Positioning System (GPS) provides an alternative source of approach guidance for aircraft.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] In the US, the Wide Area Augmentation System (WAAS) has been available in many regions to provide precision guidance to Category I standards since 2007.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] The equivalent European Geostationary Navigation Overlay Service (EGNOS) was certified for use in safety of life applications in March 2011.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] As such, the number of Cat I ILS installations may be reduced, however there are no plans in the United States to phase out any Cat II or Cat III systems.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] Local Area Augmentation System (LAAS) is under development to provide for Category III minimums or lower.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] The FAA Ground-Based Augmentation System (GBAS) office is currently working with the industry in anticipation of the certification of the first GBAS ground stations in Memphis, TN; Sydney, Australia; Bremen, Germany; Spain; and Newark, NJ.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] All four countries have installed GBAS ground stations and are involved in technical and operational evaluation activities.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] The Honeywell and FAA team obtained System Design Approval of the world's first non-federal U.S. approval for LAAS Category I at Newark Liberty International Airport, operations in September 2009 and Operational Approval on September 28, 2012.
[src:aircraft-navigation/instrument-landing-system] In Norway, a D-GPS based landing system, called SCAT-I, is in operation on some short runway airports.
[src:aircraft-navigation/non-directional-beacon] A **non-directional beacon** (**NDB**) or **non-directional radio beacon** is a radio beacon which does not include *inherent* directional information.
[src:aircraft-navigation/non-directional-beacon] Radio beacons are radio transmitters at a known location, used as an aviation or marine navigational aid.
[src:aircraft-navigation/non-directional-beacon] NDB are in contrast to directional radio beacons and other navigational aids, such as low-frequency radio range, VHF omnidirectional range (VOR) and tactical air navigation system (TACAN).
[src:aircraft-navigation/non-directional-beacon] NDB signals follow the curvature of the Earth, so they can be received at much greater distances at lower altitudes, a major advantage over VOR.
[src:aircraft-navigation/non-directional-beacon] However, NDB signals are also affected more by atmospheric conditions, mountainous terrain, coastal refraction and electrical storms, particularly at long range.
[src:aircraft-navigation/non-directional-beacon] The system, developed by United States Army Air Corps (USAAC) Captain Albert Francis Hegenberger, was used to fly the world's first instrument approach on May 9, 1932.
[src:aircraft-navigation/non-directional-beacon] NDBs used for aviation are standardised by the International Civil Aviation Organization (ICAO) Annex 10 which specifies that NDBs be operated on a frequency between 190 kHz and 1750 kHz, although normally all NDBs in North America operate between 190 kHz and 535 kHz.
[src:aircraft-navigation/non-directional-beacon] Each NDB is identified by a one, two, or three-letter Morse code callsign.
[src:aircraft-navigation/non-directional-beacon] In Canada, privately owned NDB identifiers consist of one letter and one number.
[src:aircraft-navigation/non-directional-beacon] Non-directional beacons in North America are classified by power output: "low" power rating is less than 50 watts; "medium" from 50 W to 2,000 W; and "high" at more than 2,000 W.
[src:aircraft-navigation/non-directional-beacon] The last two types are used in conjunction with an instrument landing system (ILS).
[src:aircraft-navigation/non-directional-beacon] NDB navigation consists of two parts — the *automatic direction finder* (ADF) equipment on the aircraft that detects an NDB's signal, and the NDB transmitter.
[src:aircraft-navigation/non-directional-beacon] The ADF can also locate transmitters in the standard AM medium wave broadcast band (530 kHz to 1700 kHz at 10 kHz increments in the Americas, 531 kHz to 1602 kHz at 9 kHz increments in the rest of the world).
[src:aircraft-navigation/non-directional-beacon] ADF equipment determines the direction or bearing to the NDB station relative to the aircraft by using a combination of directional and non-directional antennae to sense the direction in which the combined signal is strongest.
[src:aircraft-navigation/non-directional-beacon] This bearing may be displayed on a relative bearing indicator (RBI).
[src:aircraft-navigation/non-directional-beacon] This display looks like a compass card with a needle superimposed, except that the card is fixed with the 0 degree position corresponding to the centreline of the aircraft.
[src:aircraft-navigation/non-directional-beacon] In order to track toward an NDB (with no wind), the aircraft is flown so that the needle points to the 0 degree position.
[src:aircraft-navigation/non-directional-beacon] The aircraft will then fly directly to the NDB.
[src:aircraft-navigation/non-directional-beacon] Similarly, the aircraft will track directly away from the NDB if the needle is maintained on the 180 degree mark.
[src:aircraft-navigation/non-directional-beacon] With a crosswind, the needle must be maintained to the left or right of the 0 or 180 position by an amount corresponding to the drift due to the crosswind.
[src:aircraft-navigation/non-directional-beacon] The formula to determine the compass heading to an NDB station (in a no wind situation) is to take the relative bearing between the aircraft and the station, and add the magnetic heading of the aircraft; if the total is greater than 360 degrees, then 360 must be subtracted.
[src:aircraft-navigation/non-directional-beacon] This gives the magnetic bearing that must be flown: (RB + MH) mod 360 = MB.
[src:aircraft-navigation/non-directional-beacon] When tracking to or from an NDB, it is also usual that the aircraft track on a specific bearing.
[src:aircraft-navigation/non-directional-beacon] To do this it is necessary to correlate the RBI reading with the compass heading.
[src:aircraft-navigation/non-directional-beacon] Having determined the drift, the aircraft must be flown so that the compass heading is the required bearing adjusted for drift at the same time as the RBI reading is 0 or 180 adjusted for drift.
[src:aircraft-navigation/non-directional-beacon] An NDB may also be used to locate a position along the aircraft's current track (such as a radial path from a second NDB or a VOR).
[src:aircraft-navigation/non-directional-beacon] When the needle reaches an RBI reading corresponding to the required bearing, then the aircraft is at the position.
[src:aircraft-navigation/non-directional-beacon] However, using a separate RBI and compass, this requires considerable mental calculation to determine the appropriate relative bearing.
[src:aircraft-navigation/non-directional-beacon] To simplify this task, a compass card driven by the aircraft's magnetic compass is added to the RBI to form a radio magnetic indicator (RMI).
[src:aircraft-navigation/non-directional-beacon] The ADF needle is then referenced immediately to the aircraft's magnetic heading, which reduces the necessity for mental calculation.
[src:aircraft-navigation/non-directional-beacon] This display, along with the omni bearing indicator (OBI) for VOR/ILS information, was one of the primary radio navigation instruments prior to the introduction of the horizontal situation indicator (HSI) and subsequent digital displays used in glass cockpits.
[src:aircraft-navigation/non-directional-beacon] The principles of ADFs are not limited to NDB usage; such systems are also used to detect the locations of broadcast signals for many other purposes, such as finding emergency beacons.
[src:aircraft-navigation/non-directional-beacon] A bearing is a line passing through the station that points in a specific direction, such as 270 degrees (due west).
[src:aircraft-navigation/non-directional-beacon] NDB bearings provide a charted, consistent method for defining paths aircraft can fly.
[src:aircraft-navigation/non-directional-beacon] In this fashion, NDBs can, like VORs, define airways in the sky.
[src:aircraft-navigation/non-directional-beacon] Aircraft follow these pre-defined routes to complete a flight plan.
[src:aircraft-navigation/non-directional-beacon] Airways are numbered and standardized on charts.
[src:aircraft-navigation/non-directional-beacon] Colored airways are used for low to medium frequency stations like the NDB and are charted in brown on sectional charts.
[src:aircraft-navigation/non-directional-beacon] Green and red airways are plotted east and west, while amber and blue airways are plotted north and south.
[src:aircraft-navigation/non-directional-beacon] As of September 2022, only one colored airway is left in the continental United States, located off the coast of North Carolina and is called G13 or Green 13.
[src:aircraft-navigation/non-directional-beacon] Alaska is the only other state in the United States to make use of the colored airway systems.
[src:aircraft-navigation/non-directional-beacon] Pilots follow these routes by tracking bearings across various navigation stations, and turning at some.
[src:aircraft-navigation/non-directional-beacon] While most airways in the United States are based on VORs, NDB airways are common elsewhere, especially in the developing world and in lightly populated areas of developed countries, like the Canadian Arctic, since they can have a long range and are much less expensive to operate than VORs.
[src:aircraft-navigation/non-directional-beacon] All standard airways are plotted on aeronautical charts, such as the United States sectional charts, issued by the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration (NOAA).
[src:aircraft-navigation/non-directional-beacon] NDBs have long been used by aircraft navigators, and previously mariners, to help obtain a fix of their geographic location on the surface of the Earth.
[src:aircraft-navigation/non-directional-beacon] Fixes are computed by extending lines through known navigational reference points until they intersect.
[src:aircraft-navigation/non-directional-beacon] For visual reference points, the angles of these lines can be determined by compass; the bearings of NDB radio signals are found using radio direction finder (RDF) equipment.
[src:aircraft-navigation/non-directional-beacon] Plotting fixes in this manner allow crews to determine their position.
[src:aircraft-navigation/non-directional-beacon] This usage is important in situations where other navigational equipment, such as VORs with distance measuring equipment (DME), have failed.
[src:aircraft-navigation/non-directional-beacon] In marine navigation, NDBs may still be useful should Global Positioning System (GPS) reception fail.
[src:aircraft-navigation/non-directional-beacon] Flies that heading, timing how long it takes to cross a specific number of NDB bearings.
[src:aircraft-navigation/non-directional-beacon] A runway equipped with NDB or VOR (or both) as the only navigation aid is called a non-precision approach runway; if it is equipped with ILS, it is called a precision approach runway.
[src:aircraft-navigation/non-directional-beacon] NDBs are most commonly used as markers or "locators" for an instrument landing system (ILS) approach or standard approach.
[src:aircraft-navigation/non-directional-beacon] NDBs may designate the starting area for an ILS approach or a path to follow for a standard terminal arrival route, or STAR.
[src:aircraft-navigation/non-directional-beacon] In the United States, an NDB is often combined with the outer marker beacon in the ILS approach (called a locator outer marker, or LOM); in Canada, low-powered NDBs have replaced marker beacons entirely.
[src:aircraft-navigation/non-directional-beacon] Marker beacons on ILS approaches are now being phased out worldwide with DME ranges or GPS signals used, instead, to delineate the different segments of the approach.
[src:aircraft-navigation/non-directional-beacon] German Navy U-boats during World War II were equipped with a Telefunken Spez 2113S homing beacon.
[src:aircraft-navigation/non-directional-beacon] This transmitter could operate on 100 kHz to 1500 kHz with a power of 150 W.
[src:aircraft-navigation/non-directional-beacon] It was used to send the submarine's location to other submarines or aircraft, which were equipped with DF receivers and loop antennas.
[src:aircraft-navigation/non-directional-beacon] NDBs typically operate in the frequency range from 190 kHz to 535 kHz (although they are allocated frequencies from 190 to 1750 kHz) and transmit a carrier modulated by either 400 or 1020 Hz.
[src:aircraft-navigation/non-directional-beacon] NDBs can also be collocated with a DME in a similar installation for the ILS as the outer marker, only in this case, they function as the inner marker.
[src:aircraft-navigation/non-directional-beacon] NDB owners are mostly governmental agencies and airport authorities.
[src:aircraft-navigation/non-directional-beacon] NDB antennas are usually too short for resonance at the frequency they operate – typically perhaps 20 metres length compared to a wavelength around 1000 m.
[src:aircraft-navigation/non-directional-beacon] Therefore, they require a suitable matching network that may consist of an inductor and a capacitor to "tune" the antenna.
[src:aircraft-navigation/non-directional-beacon] Vertical NDB antennas may also have a T-antenna, nicknamed a *top hat*, which is an umbrella-like structure designed to add loading at the end and improve its radiating efficiency.
[src:aircraft-navigation/non-directional-beacon] Usually a ground plane or counterpoise is connected underneath the antenna.
[src:aircraft-navigation/non-directional-beacon] from the transmitter, especially just before sunrise and just after sunset.
[src:aircraft-navigation/non-directional-beacon] Because the returning sky waves travel over a different path, they have a different phase from the ground wave.
[src:aircraft-navigation/non-directional-beacon] This has the effect of suppressing the aerial signal in a fairly random manner.
[src:aircraft-navigation/non-directional-beacon] The needle on the indicator will start wandering.
[src:aircraft-navigation/non-directional-beacon] The indication will be most erratic during twilight at dusk and dawn.
[src:aircraft-navigation/non-directional-beacon] High terrain like mountains and cliffs can reflect radio waves, giving erroneous readings.
[src:aircraft-navigation/non-directional-beacon] circulating within a storm cloud, generate wideband noise.
[src:aircraft-navigation/non-directional-beacon] This high power noise may affect the accuracy of the ADF bearing.
[src:aircraft-navigation/non-directional-beacon] Lightning, due to the high power output will cause the needle of the RMI/RBI to point for a moment to the bearing of the lightning.
[src:aircraft-navigation/non-directional-beacon] Radio waves speed up over water, causing the wave front to bend away from its normal path and pull it towards the coast.
[src:aircraft-navigation/non-directional-beacon] Refraction is negligible perpendicular (90°) to the coast, but increases as the angle of incidence decreases.
[src:aircraft-navigation/non-directional-beacon] The effect can be minimised by flying higher or by using NDBs situated nearer the coast.
[src:aircraft-navigation/non-directional-beacon] Due to congestion of stations in the LF and MF bands, there is the possibility of interference from stations on or near the same frequency.
[src:aircraft-navigation/non-directional-beacon] By day, the use of an NDB within the DOC will normally afford protection from interference.
[src:aircraft-navigation/non-directional-beacon] However, at night one can expect interference even within the DOC because of skywave contamination from stations out of range by day.
[src:aircraft-navigation/non-directional-beacon] Therefore, positive identification of the NDB at night should always be carried out.
[src:aircraft-navigation/non-directional-beacon] During banking turns in an aircraft, the horizontal part of the loop aerial will no longer be horizontal and detect a signal.
[src:aircraft-navigation/non-directional-beacon] This causes displacement of the null in a way similar to the night effect giving an erroneous reading on the indicator which means that the pilot should not obtain a bearing unless the aircraft is wings-level.
[src:aircraft-navigation/non-directional-beacon] While pilots study these effects during initial training, trying to compensate for them in flight is very difficult; instead, pilots generally simply choose a heading that seems to average out any fluctuations.
[src:aircraft-navigation/non-directional-beacon] Besides their use in aircraft navigation, NDBs are also popular with long-distance radio enthusiasts (*DXers*).
[src:aircraft-navigation/non-directional-beacon] Because NDBs are generally low-power (usually 25 watts, some can be up to 5 kW), they normally cannot be heard over long distances, but favorable conditions in the ionosphere can allow NDB signals to travel much farther than normal.
[src:aircraft-navigation/non-directional-beacon] Because of this, radio DXers interested in picking up distant signals enjoy listening to faraway NDBs.
[src:aircraft-navigation/non-directional-beacon] Also, since the band allocated to NDBs is free of broadcast stations and their associated interference, and because most NDBs do little more than transmit their Morse code callsign, they are very easy to identify, making NDB monitoring an active niche within the DXing hobby.
[src:aircraft-navigation/non-directional-beacon] In North America, the NDB band is from 190 to 435 kHz and from 510 to 530 kHz.
[src:aircraft-navigation/non-directional-beacon] In Europe, there is a longwave broadcasting band from 150 to 280 kHz, so the European NDB band is from 280 kHz to 530 kHz with a gap between 495 and 505 kHz because 500 kHz was the international maritime distress (emergency) frequency.
[src:aircraft-navigation/non-directional-beacon] The beacons that transmit between 510 kHz and 530 kHz can sometimes be heard on AM radios that can tune below the beginning of the medium wave (MW) broadcast band.
[src:aircraft-navigation/non-directional-beacon] However, reception of NDBs generally requires a radio receiver that can receive frequencies below 530 kHz.
[src:aircraft-navigation/non-directional-beacon] Often "general coverage" shortwave radios receive all frequencies from 150 kHz to 30 MHz, and so can tune to the frequencies of NDBs.
[src:aircraft-navigation/non-directional-beacon] Specialized techniques (receiver preselectors, noise limiters and filters) are required for the reception of very weak signals from remote beacons.
[src:aircraft-navigation/non-directional-beacon] The best time to hear NDBs that are very far away is the last three hours before sunrise.
[src:aircraft-navigation/non-directional-beacon] Reception of NDBs is also usually best during the fall and winter because during the spring and summer, there is more atmospheric noise on the LF and MF bands.
[src:aircraft-navigation/non-directional-beacon] As the adoption of satellite navigation systems such as GPS progressed, several countries began to decommission beacon installations such as NDBs and VOR.
[src:aircraft-navigation/non-directional-beacon] The policy has caused controversy in the aviation industry.
[src:aircraft-navigation/non-directional-beacon] Airservices Australia began shutting down a number of ground-based navigation aids in May 2016, including NDBs, VORs and DMEs.
[src:aircraft-navigation/non-directional-beacon] In the United States as of 2017, there were more than 1,300 NDBs, of which fewer than 300 were owned by the Federal Government.
[src:aircraft-navigation/non-directional-beacon] The FAA had begun decommissioning stand-alone NDBs.
[src:aircraft-navigation/non-directional-beacon] As of April 2018, the FAA had disabled 23 ground-based navaids including NDBs, and plans to shut down more than 300 by 2025.
[src:aircraft-navigation/non-directional-beacon] The FAA has no sustaining or acquisition system for NDBs and plans to phase out the existing NDBs through attrition, citing decreased pilot reliance on NDBs as more pilots use VOR and GPS navigation.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] RDF systems can be used with any radio source, although very long wavelengths (low frequencies) require very large antennas, and are generally used only on ground-based systems.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] These wavelengths are nevertheless used for marine radio navigation as they can travel very long distances "over the horizon", which is valuable for ships when the line-of-sight may be only a few tens of kilometres.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] For aerial use, where the horizon may extend to hundreds of kilometres, higher frequencies can be used, allowing the use of much smaller antennas.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] An automatic direction finder, which could be tuned to radio beacons called non-directional beacons or commercial AM radio broadcasters, was in the 20th century a feature of most aircraft, but is being phased out.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] For the military, RDF is a key tool of signals intelligence.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] The ability to locate the position of an enemy transmitter has been invaluable since World War I, and played a key role in World War II's Battle of the Atlantic.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] It is estimated that the UK's advanced "huff-duff" systems were directly or indirectly responsible for 24% of all U-boats sunk during the war.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] Modern systems often used phased array antennas to allow rapid beamforming for highly accurate results, and are part of a larger electronic warfare suite.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] Early radio direction finders used mechanically rotated antennas that compared signal strengths, and several electronic versions of the same concept followed.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] Modern systems use the comparison of phase or doppler techniques which are generally simpler to automate.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] Early British radar sets were referred to as RDF, which is often stated was a deception.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] In fact, the Chain Home systems used large RDF receivers to determine directions.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] Later radar systems generally used a single antenna for broadcast and reception, and determined direction from the direction the antenna was facing.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] The earliest experiments in RDF were carried out in 1888 when Heinrich Hertz discovered the directionality of an open loop of wire used as an antenna.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] When the antenna was aligned so it pointed at the signal it produced maximum gain, and produced zero signal when face on.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] This meant there was always an ambiguity in the location of the signal: it would produce the same output if the signal was in front or back of the antenna.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] Later experimenters also used dipole antennas, which worked in the opposite sense, reaching maximum gain at right angles and zero when aligned.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] RDF systems using mechanically swung loop or dipole antennas were common by the turn of the 20th century.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] Prominent examples were patented by John Stone Stone in 1902 (U.S.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] Patent 771,819), among many other examples.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] By the early 1900s, many experimenters were looking for ways to use this concept for locating the position of a transmitter.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] Early radio systems generally used medium wave and longwave signals.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] Longwave in particular had good long-distance transmission characteristics due to their limited interaction with the ground, and thereby provided excellent great circle route ground wave propagation that pointed directly to the transmitter.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] Methods of performing RDF on longwave signals was a major area of research during the 1900s and 1910s.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] Antennas are generally sensitive to signals only when they have a length that is a significant portion of the wavelength, or larger.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] Most antennas are at least 1⁄4 of the wavelength, more commonly 1⁄2 – the half-wave dipole is a very common design.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] For longwave use, this resulted in loop antennas tens of feet on a side, often with more than one loop connected together to improve the signal.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] Another solution to this problem was developed by the Marconi company in 1905.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] This consisted of a number of horizontal wires or rods arranged to point outward from a common center point.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] A movable switch could connect opposite pairs of these wires to form a dipole, and by rotating the switch the operator could hunt for the strongest signal.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] The US Navy overcame this problem, to a point, by mounting antennas on ships and sailing in circles.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] Such systems were unwieldily and impractical for many uses.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] A key improvement in the RDF concept was introduced by Ettore Bellini and Alessandro Tosi in 1909 (U.S.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] Their system used two such antennas, typically triangular loops, arranged at right angles.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] The signals from the antennas were sent into coils wrapped around a wooden frame about the size of a drink can, where the signals were re-created in the area between the coils.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] A separate loop antenna located in this area could then be used to hunt for the direction, without moving the main antennas.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] This made RDF so much more practical that it was soon being used for navigation on a wide scale, often as the first form of aerial navigation available, with ground stations homing in on the aircraft's radio set.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] Bellini–Tosi direction finders were widespread from the 1920s into the 1950s.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] Early RDF systems were useful largely for long wave signals.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] These signals are able to travel very long distances, which made them useful for long-range navigation.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] However, when the same technique was being applied to higher frequencies, unexpected difficulties arose due to the reflection of high frequency signals from the ionosphere.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] The RDF station might now receive the same signal from two or more locations, especially during the day, which caused serious problems trying to determine the location.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] This led to the 1919 introduction of the Adcock antenna (UK Patent 130,490), which consisted of four separate monopole antennas instead of two loops, eliminating the horizontal components and thus filtering out the sky waves being reflected down from the ionosphere.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] Adcock antennas were widely used with Bellini–Tosi detectors from the 1920s on.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] The US Army Air Corps in 1931 tested a primitive radio compass that used commercial stations as the beacon.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] A major improvement in the RDF technique was introduced by Robert Watson-Watt as part of his experiments to locate lightning strikes as a method to indicate the direction of thunderstorms for sailors and airmen.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] He had long worked with conventional RDF systems, but these were difficult to use with the fleeting signals from the lightning.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] He had early on suggested the use of an oscilloscope to display these near instantly, but was unable to find one while working at the Met Office.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] When the office was moved, his new location at a radio research station provided him with both an Adcock antenna and a suitable oscilloscope, and he presented his new system in 1926.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] In spite of the system being presented publicly, and its measurements widely reported in the UK, its impact on the art of RDF seems to be strangely subdued.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] Development was limited until the mid-1930s, when the various British forces began widespread development and deployment of these "high-frequency direction finding", or "huff-duff" systems.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] To avoid RDF, the Germans had developed a method of broadcasting short messages under 30 seconds, less than the 60 seconds that a trained Bellini-Tosi operator would need to determine the direction.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] However, this was useless against huff-duff systems, which located the signal with reasonable accuracy in seconds.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] The Germans did not become aware of this problem until the middle of the war, and did not take any serious steps to address it until 1944.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] By that time huff-duff had helped in about one-quarter of all successful attacks on the U-boat fleet.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] Several developments in electronics during and after the Second World War led to greatly improved methods of comparing the phase of signals.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] In addition, the phase-locked loop (PLL) allowed for easy tuning in of signals, which would not drift.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] Improved vacuum tubes and the introduction of the transistor allowed much higher frequencies to be used economically, which led to widespread use of VHF and UHF signals.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] All of these changes led to new methods of RDF, and its much more widespread use.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] In particular, the ability to compare the phase of signals led to phase-comparison RDF, which is perhaps the most widely used technique today.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] In this system the loop antenna is replaced with a single square-shaped ferrite core, with loops wound around two perpendicular sides.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] Signals from the loops are sent into a phase comparison circuit, whose output phase directly indicates the direction of the signal.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] By sending this to any manner of display, and locking the signal using PLL, the direction to the broadcaster can be continuously displayed.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] Operation consists solely of tuning in the station, and is so automatic that these systems are normally referred to as automatic direction finder.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] Other systems have been developed where more accuracy is required.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] Pseudo-doppler radio direction finder systems use a series of small dipole antennas arranged in a ring and use electronic switching to rapidly select dipoles to feed into the receiver.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] The resulting signal is processed and produces an audio tone.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] The phase of that audio tone, compared to the antenna rotation, depends on the direction of the signal.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] Doppler RDF systems have widely replaced the huff-duff system for location of fleeting signals.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] The various procedures for radio direction finding to determine position at sea are no longer part of the maritime safety system GMDSS, which has been in force since 1999.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] The striking cross frame antenna with attached auxiliary antenna can only be found on the signal masts of some older ships because they do not interfere there and dismantling would be too expensive.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] Modern positioning methods such as GPS, DGPS, radar and the now-outdated Loran C have radio direction finding methods that are imprecise for today's needs.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] Radio direction finding networks also no longer exist.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] However rescue vessels, such as RNLI lifeboats in the UK, and Search and Rescue helicopters have direction finding receivers for marine VHF signals and the 121.5 MHz homing signals incorporated in EPIRB and PLB beacons, although modern GPS-EPIRBS and AIS beacons are slowly making these redundant.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] A **radio direction finder** (**RDF**) is a device for finding the direction, or *bearing*, to a radio source.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] The act of measuring the direction is known as **radio direction finding** or sometimes simply **direction finding** (**DF**).
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] Using two or more measurements from different locations, the location of an unknown transmitter can be determined; alternately, using two or more measurements of known transmitters, the location of a vehicle can be determined.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] RDF is widely used as a radio navigation system, especially with boats and aircraft.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] RDF systems can be used with any radio source, although the size of the receiver antennas are a function of the wavelength of the signal; very long wavelengths (low frequencies) require very large antennas, and are generally used only on ground-based systems.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] These wavelengths are nevertheless very useful for marine navigation as they can travel very long distances and "over the horizon", which is valuable for ships when the line-of-sight may be only a few tens of kilometres.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] For aircraft, where the horizon at altitude may extend to hundreds of kilometres, higher frequencies can be used, allowing much smaller antennas.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] An automatic direction finder, often capable of being tuned to commercial AM radio transmitters, is a feature of almost all modern aircraft.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] For the military, RDF systems are a key component of signals intelligence systems and methodologies.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] The ability to locate the position of an enemy transmitter has been invaluable since World War I, and it played a key role in World War II's Battle of the Atlantic.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] Modern systems often use phased array antennas to allow rapid beam forming for highly accurate results.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] These are generally integrated into a wider electronic warfare suite.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] Several distinct generations of RDF systems have been used over time, following new developments in electronics.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] Early systems used mechanically rotated antennas that compared signal strengths from different directions, and several electronic versions of the same concept followed.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] Modern pseudo-Doppler direction finder systems consist of a number of small antennas fixed to a circular card, with all of the processing performed by software.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] Early British radar sets were also referred to as RDF, which was a deception tactic.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] However, the terminology was not inaccurate; the Chain Home systems used separate omnidirectional broadcasters and large RDF receivers to determine the location of the targets.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] In one type of direction finding, a directional antenna is used which is more sensitive in certain directions than in others.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] Many antenna designs exhibit this property.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] For example, a Yagi antenna has quite pronounced directionality, so the source of a transmission can be determined by pointing it in the direction where the maximum signal level is obtained.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] Since the directional characteristics can be very broad, large antennas may be used to improve precision, or null techniques used to improve angular resolution.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] A simple form of directional antenna is the loop aerial.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] This consists of an open loop of wire on an insulating frame, or a metal ring that forms the antenna's loop element itself; often the diameter of the loop is a tenth of a wavelength or smaller at the target frequency.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] Such an antenna will be *least* sensitive to signals that are perpendicular to its face and *most* responsive to those arriving edge-on.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] This is caused by the phase of the received signal: The difference in electrical phase along the rim of the loop at any instant causes a difference in the voltages induced on either side of the loop.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] Turning the plane of the loop to "face" the signal so that the arriving phases are identical around the entire rim will not induce any current flow in the loop.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] So simply turning the antenna to produce a *minimum* in the desired signal will establish two possible directions (front and back) from which the radio waves could be arriving.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] Since the null direction gives a clearer indication of the signal direction – the null is "sharper" than the max – with loop aerial the null direction is used to locate a signal source.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] A "sense antenna" is used to resolve the two direction possibilities; the sense aerial is a non-directional antenna configured to have the same sensitivity as the loop aerial.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] By adding the steady signal from the sense aerial to the alternating signal from the loop signal as it rotates, there is now only one position as the loop rotates 360° at which there is zero current.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] This acts as a phase reference point, allowing the correct null point to be identified, removing the 180° ambiguity.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] A dipole antenna exhibits similar properties, as a small loop, although its null direction is not as "sharp".
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] The Yagi-Uda antenna is familiar as the common VHF or UHF television aerial.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] A Yagi antenna uses multiple dipole elements, which include "reflector" and "director" dipole elements.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] The "reflector" is the longest dipole element and blocks nearly all the signal coming from behind it, hence a Yagi has no front vs. back directional ambiguity: The maximum signal only occurs when the narrowest end of the Yagi is aimed in the direction from which the radio waves are arriving.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] With a sufficient number of shorter "director" elements, a Yagi's maximum direction can be made to approach the sharpness of a small loop's null.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] For much higher frequencies still, such as millimeter waves and microwaves, parabolic antennas or "dish" antennas can be used.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] Dish antennas are highly directional, with the parabolic shape directing received signals from a very narrow angle into a small receiving element mounted at the focus of the parabola.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] More sophisticated techniques such as phased arrays are generally used for highly accurate direction finding systems.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] The modern systems are called goniometers by analogy to WW II directional circuits used to measure direction by comparing the differences in two or more matched reference antennas' received signals, used in old signals intelligence (SIGINT).
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] A modern helicopter-mounted direction finding system was designed by ESL Incorporated for the U.S.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] Time difference of arrival techniques compare the arrival time of a radio wave at two or more different antennas and deduce the direction of arrival from this timing information.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] This method can use mechanically simple non-moving omnidirectional antenna elements fed into a multiple channel receiver system.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] One form of radio direction finding works by comparing the signal strength of a directional antenna pointing in different directions.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] At first, this system was used by land and marine-based radio operators, using a simple rotatable loop antenna linked to a degree indicator.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] This system was later adopted for both ships and aircraft, and was widely used in the 1930s and 1940s.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] On pre-World War II aircraft, RDF antennas are easy to identify as the circular loops mounted above or below the fuselage.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] Later loop antenna designs were enclosed in an aerodynamic, teardrop-shaped fairing.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] In ships and small boats, RDF receivers first employed large metal loop antennas, similar to aircraft, but usually mounted atop a portable battery-powered receiver.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] This null was symmetrical, and thus identified both the correct degree heading marked on the radio's compass rose as well as its 180-degree opposite.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] While this information provided a baseline from the station to the ship or aircraft, the navigator still needed to know beforehand if he was to the east or west of the station in order to avoid plotting a course 180-degrees in the wrong direction.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] By taking bearings to two or more broadcast stations and plotting the intersecting bearings, the navigator could locate the relative position of his ship or aircraft.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] Later, RDF sets were equipped with rotatable ferrite loopstick antennas, which made the sets more portable and less bulky.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] Some were later partially automated by means of a motorized antenna (ADF).
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] A key breakthrough was the introduction of a secondary vertical whip or 'sense' antenna that substantiated the correct bearing and allowed the navigator to avoid plotting a bearing 180 degrees opposite the actual heading.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] Navy RDF model SE 995 which used a sense antenna was in use during World War I.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] After World War II, there were many small and large firms making direction finding equipment for mariners, including Apelco, Aqua Guide, Bendix, Gladding (and its marine division, Pearce-Simpson), Ray Jefferson, Raytheon, and Sperry.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] By the 1960s, many of these radios were actually made by Japanese electronics manufacturers, such as Panasonic, Fuji Onkyo, and Koden Electronics Co., Ltd.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] In aircraft equipment, Bendix and Sperry-Rand were two of the larger manufacturers of RDF radios and navigation instruments.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] Single-channel DF uses a multi-antenna array with a single channel radio receiver.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] This approach to DF offers some advantages and drawbacks.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] Since it only uses one receiver, mobility and lower power consumption are benefits.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] Without the ability to look at each antenna simultaneously (which would be the case if one were to use multiple receivers, also known as N-channel DF) more complex operations need to occur at the antenna in order to present the signal to the receiver.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] The two main categories that a single channel DF algorithm falls into are *amplitude comparison* and *phase comparison*.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] Some algorithms can be hybrids of the two.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] The pseudo-doppler technique is a phase based DF method that produces a bearing estimate on the received signal by measuring the doppler shift induced on the signal by sampling around the elements of a circular array.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] The original method used a single antenna that physically moved in a circle but the modern approach uses a multi-antenna circular array with each antenna sampled in succession.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] The Watson-Watt technique uses two antenna pairs to perform an amplitude comparison on the incoming signal.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] The popular Watson-Watt method uses an array of two orthogonal coils (magnetic dipoles) in the horizontal plane, often completed with an omnidirectional vertically polarized electric dipole to resolve 180° ambiguities.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] The Adcock antenna array uses a pair of monopole or dipole antennas that takes the vector difference of the received signal at each antenna so that there is only one output from each pair of antennas.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] Two of these pairs are co-located but perpendicularly oriented to produce what can be referred to as the N–S (North-South) and E–W (East-West) signals that will then be passed to the receiver.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] In the receiver, the bearing angle can then be computed by taking the arctangent of the ratio of the N–S to E–W signal.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] The basic principle of the correlative interferometer consists in comparing the measured phase differences with the phase differences obtained for a DF antenna system of known configuration at a known wave angle (reference data set).
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] For this, at least three antenna elements (with omnidirectional reception characteristics) must form a non-collinear basis.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] The comparison is made for different azimuth and elevation values of the reference data set.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] The bearing result is obtained from a correlative and stochastic evaluation for which the correlation coefficient is at a maximum.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] If the direction finding antenna elements have a directional antenna pattern, then the amplitude may be included in the comparison.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] Typically, the correlative interferometer DF system consists of more than five antenna elements.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] These are scanned one after the other via a specific switching matrix.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] In a multi-channel DF system n antenna elements are combined with m receiver channels to improve the DF-system performance.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] Similar beacons located in coastal areas are also used for maritime radio navigation, as almost every ship was equipped with a direction finder (Appleyard 1988).
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] Very few maritime radio navigation beacons remain active today (2008) as ships have abandoned navigation via RDF in favor of GPS navigation.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] In the United Kingdom a radio direction finding service is available on 121.5 MHz and 243.0 MHz to aircraft pilots who are in distress or are experiencing difficulties.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] The service is based on a number of radio DF units located at civil and military airports and certain HM Coastguard stations.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] These stations can obtain a "fix" of the aircraft and transmit it by radio to the pilot.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] Radio transmitters for air and sea navigation are known as *beacons* and are the radio equivalent to a lighthouse.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] The transmitter sends a Morse Code transmission on a Long wave (150 – 400 kHz) or Medium wave (520 – 1720 kHz) frequency incorporating the station's identifier that is used to confirm the station and its operational status.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] Since these radio signals are broadcast in all directions (omnidirectional) during the day, the signal itself does not include direction information, and these beacons are therefore referred to as non-directional beacons, or **NDBs**.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] As the commercial medium wave broadcast band lies within the frequency capability of most RDF units, these stations and their transmitters can also be used for navigational fixes.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] While these commercial radio stations can be useful due to their high power and location near major cities, there may be several miles between the location of the station and its transmitter, which can reduce the accuracy of the 'fix' when approaching the broadcast city.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] A second factor is that some AM radio stations are omnidirectional during the day, and switch to a reduced power, directional signal at night.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] RDF was once the primary form of aircraft and marine navigation.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] Strings of beacons formed "airways" from airport to airport, while marine NDBs and commercial AM broadcast stations provided navigational assistance to small watercraft approaching a landfall.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] In the United States, commercial AM radio stations were required to broadcast their station identifier once per hour for use by pilots and mariners as an aid to navigation.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] In the 1950s, aviation NDBs were augmented by the VOR system, in which the direction to the beacon can be extracted from the signal itself, hence the distinction with non-directional beacons.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] Use of marine NDBs was largely supplanted in North America by the development of LORAN in the 1970s.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] Today many NDBs have been decommissioned in favor of faster and far more accurate GPS navigational systems.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] However the low cost of ADF and RDF systems, and the continued existence of AM broadcast stations (as well as navigational beacons in countries outside North America) has allowed these devices to continue to function, primarily for use in small boats, as an adjunct or backup to GPS.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] In World War II considerable effort was expended on identifying secret transmitters in the United Kingdom (UK) by direction finding.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] The work was undertaken by the Radio Security Service (RSS also MI8).
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] Initially three U Adcock HF DF stations were set up in 1939 by the General Post Office.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] With the declaration of war, MI5 and RSS developed this into a larger network.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] One of the problems with providing coverage of an area the size of the UK was installing sufficient DF stations to cover the entire area to receive skywave signals reflected back from the ionised layers in the upper atmosphere.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] Even with the expanded network, some areas were not adequately covered and for this reason up to 1700 voluntary interceptors (radio amateurs) were recruited to detect illicit transmissions by ground wave.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] In addition to the fixed stations, RSS ran a fleet of mobile DF vehicles around the UK.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] If a transmitter was identified by the fixed DF stations or voluntary interceptors, the mobile units were sent to the area to home in on the source.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] The mobile units were HF Adcock systems.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] By 1941 only a couple of illicit transmitters had been identified in the UK; these were German agents that had been "turned" and were transmitting under MI5 control.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] Many illicit transmissions had been logged emanating from German agents in occupied and neutral countries in Europe.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] The traffic became a valuable source of intelligence, so the control of RSS was subsequently passed to MI6 who were responsible for secret intelligence originating from outside the UK.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] The direction finding and interception operation increased in volume and importance until 1945.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] The HF Adcock stations consisted of four 10 m vertical antennas surrounding a small wooden operators hut containing a receiver and a radio-goniometer which was adjusted to obtain the bearing.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] MF stations were also used which used four guyed 30 m lattice tower antennas.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] In 1941, RSS began experimenting with spaced loop direction finders, developed by the Marconi company and the UK National Physical Laboratories.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] These consisted of two parallel loops 1 to 2 m square on the ends of a rotatable 3 to 8 m beam.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] The angle of the beam was combined with results from a radiogoniometer to provide a bearing.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] The bearing obtained was considerably sharper than that obtained with the U Adcock system, but there were ambiguities which prevented the installation of 7 proposed S.L DF systems.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] The operator of an SL system was in a metal underground tank below the antennas.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] Seven underground tanks were installed, but only two SL systems were installed at Wymondham, Norfolk and Weaverthorp in Yorkshire.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] Problems were encountered resulting in the remaining five underground tanks being fitted with Adcock systems.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] The rotating SL antenna was turned by hand which meant successive measurements were a lot slower than turning the dial of a goniometer.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] Another experimental spaced loop station was built near Aberdeen in 1942 for the Air Ministry with a semi-underground concrete bunker.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] This, too, was abandoned because of operating difficulties.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] By 1944, a mobile version of the spaced loop had been developed and was used by RSS in France following the D-Day invasion of Normandy.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] The US military used a shore based version of the spaced loop DF in World War II called "DAB".
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] The loops were placed at the ends of a beam, all of which was located inside a wooden hut with the electronics in a large cabinet with cathode-ray-tube display at the centre of the beam and everything being supported on a central axis.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] The beam was rotated manually by the operator.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] The Royal Navy introduced a variation on the shore based HF DF stations in 1944 to track U-boats in the North Atlantic.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] They built groups of five DF stations, so that bearings from individual stations in the group could be combined and a mean taken.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] Four such groups were built in Britain at Ford End, Essex; Goonhavern, Cornwall; and Anstruther and Bowermadden in the Scottish Highlands.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] Groups were also built in Iceland, Nova Scotia, and Jamaica.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] The anticipated improvements were not realised but later statistical work improved the system and the Goonhavern and Ford End groups continued to be used during the Cold War.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] The Royal Navy also deployed direction finding equipment on ships tasked to anti-submarine warfare in order to try to locate German submarines, e.g.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] Captain class frigates were fitted with a medium frequency direction finding antenna (MF/DF) (the antenna was fitted in front of the bridge) and high frequency direction finding (HF/DF, "Huffduff") Type FH 4 antenna (the antenna was fitted on top of the mainmast).
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] A comprehensive reference on World War II wireless direction finding was written by Roland Keen, who was head of the engineering department of RSS at Hanslope Park.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] The DF systems mentioned here are described in detail in his 1947 book *Wireless Direction Finding*.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] At the end of World War II a number of RSS DF stations continued to operate into the Cold War under the control of GCHQ the British SIGINT organisation.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] Most direction finding effort within the UK now (2009) is directed towards locating unauthorised "pirate" FM broadcast radio transmissions.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] A network of remotely operated VHF direction finders are used mainly located around the major cities.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] The transmissions from mobile telephone handsets are also located by a form of direction finding using the comparative signal strength at the surrounding local "cell" receivers.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] This technique is often offered as evidence in UK criminal prosecutions and, almost certainly, for SIGINT purposes.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] Emergency position-indicating rescue beacons are widely deployed on civil aircraft and ships.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] Historically emergency location transmitters only sent a tone signal and relied on direction finding by search aircraft to locate the beacon.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] Modern emergency beacons transmit a unique identification signal that can include GPS location data that can aid in finding the exact location of the transmitter.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] Avalanche transceivers operate on a standard 457 kHz, and are designed to help locate people and equipment buried by avalanches.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] Since the power of the beacon is so low the directionality of the radio signal is dominated by small scale field effects and can be quite complicated to locate.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] Location of radio-tagged animals by triangulation is a widely applied research technique for studying the movement of animals.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] The technique was first used in the early 1960s, when radio transmitters and batteries became small enough to attach to wildlife, and is now widely deployed for a variety of wildlife studies.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] Most tracking of wild animals that have been affixed with radio transmitter equipment is done by a field researcher using a handheld radio direction finding device.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] When the researcher wants to locate a particular animal, the location of the animal can be triangulated by determining the direction to the transmitter from several locations.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] Phased arrays and other advanced antenna techniques are utilized to track launches of rocket systems and their resulting trajectories.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] These systems can be used for defensive purposes and also to gain intelligence on operation of missiles belonging to other nations.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] These same techniques are used for detection and tracking of conventional aircraft.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] Earth-based receivers can detect radio signals emanating from distant stars or regions of ionized gas.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] Receivers in radio telescopes can detect the general direction of such naturally occurring radio sources, sometimes correlating their location with objects visible with optical telescopes.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] Accurate measurement of the arrival time of radio impulses by two radio telescopes at different places on Earth, or the same telescope at different times in Earth's orbit around the Sun, may also allow estimation of the distance to a radio object.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] Events hosted by groups and organizations that involve the use of radio direction finding skills to locate transmitters at unknown locations have been popular since the end of World War II.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] Many of these events were first promoted in order to practice the use of radio direction finding techniques for disaster response and civil defense purposes, or to practice locating the source of radio frequency interference.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] The most popular form of the sport, worldwide, is known as amateur radio direction finding (ARDF).
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] DF techniques for microwave frequencies were developed in the 1940s, in response to the growing numbers of transmitters operating at these higher frequencies.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] This required the design of new antennas and receivers for the DF systems.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] In Naval systems, the DF capability became part of the Electronic Support Measures suite (ESM), where the directional information obtained augments other signal identification processes.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] In aircraft, a DF system provides additional information for the Radar Warning Receiver (RWR).
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] Over time, it became necessary to improve the performance of microwave DF systems in order to counter the evasive tactics being employed by some operators, such as low-probability-of-intercept radars and covert Data links.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] Earlier in the century, vacuum tubes (thermionic valves) were used extensively in transmitters and receivers, but their high frequency performance was limited by transit time effects.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] Even with special processes to reduce lead lengths, such as frame grid construction, as used in the EF50, and planar construction, very few tubes could operate above UHF.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] Intensive research work was carried out in the 1930s in order to develop transmitting tubes specifically for the microwave band which included, in particular, the klystron the cavity magnetron and the travelling wave tube (TWT).
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] Following the successful development of these tubes, large scale production occurred in the following decade.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] Microwave signals have short wavelengths, which results in greatly improved target resolution when compared to RF systems.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] This permits better identification of multiple targets and, also, gives improved directional accuracy.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] Also, the antennas are small so they can be assembled into compact arrays and, in addition, they can achieve well defined beam patterns which can provide the narrow beams with high gain favoured by radars and Data links.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] Other advantages of the newly available microwave band were the absence of fading (often a problem in the Shortwave radio (SW) band) and great increase in signal spectrum, compared to the congested RF bands already in use.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] In addition to being able to accommodate many more signals, the ability to use Spread spectrum and frequency hopping techniques now became possible.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] Once microwave techniques had become established, there was rapid expansion into the band by both military and commercial users.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] Antennas for DF have to meet different requirements from those for a radar or communication link, where an antenna with a narrow beam and high gain is usually an advantage.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] However, when carrying out direction finding, the bearing of the source may be unknown, so antennas with wide beamwidths are usually chosen, even though they have lower antenna boresight gain.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] In addition, the antennas are required to cover a wide band of frequencies.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] The figure shows the normalized polar plot of a typical antenna gain characteristic, in the horizontal plane.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] The half-power beamwidth of the main beam is 2 × Ψ0.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] Preferably, when using amplitude comparison methods for direction finding, the main lobe should approximate to a Gaussian characteristic.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] Although the figure also shows the presence of sidelobes, these are not a major concern when antennas are used in a DF array.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] Typically, the boresight gain of an antenna is related to the beam width.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] For a rectangular horn, ${\text{Gain}}\approx {\frac {30,\!000}{\mathrm {BW} _{h}\times \mathrm {BW} _{v}}}$ where BW*h* and BW*v* are the horizontal and vertical antenna beamwidths, respectively, in degrees.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] Two antenna types, popular for DF, are cavity-backed spirals and horn antennas.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] Spiral antennas are capable of very wide bandwidths and have a nominal half-power beamwidth of about 70deg, making them very suitable for antenna arrays containing 4, 5 or 6 antennas.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] For larger arrays, needing narrower beamwidths, horns may be used.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] The bandwidths of horn antennas may be increased by using double-ridged waveguide feeds and by using horns with internal ridges.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] Early microwave receivers were usually simple "crystal-video" receivers, which use a crystal detector followed by a video amplifier with a compressive characteristic to extend the dynamic range.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] Such a receiver was wideband but not very sensitive.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] However, this lack of sensitivity could be tolerated because of the "range advantage" enjoyed by the DF receiver (see below).
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] The klystron and TWT are linear devices and so, in principle, could be used as receiver preamplifiers.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] However, the klystron was quite unsuitable as it was a narrow-band device and extremely noisy and the TWT, although potentially more suitable, has poor matching characteristics and large bulk, which made it unsuitable for multi-channel systems using a preamplifier per antenna.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] However, a system has been demonstrated, in which a single TWT preamplifier selectively selects signals from an antenna array.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] Transistors suitable for microwave frequencies became available towards the end of the 1950s.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] The first of these was the metal oxide semiconductor field effect transistor (MOSFET).
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] Others followed, for example, the metal-semiconductor field-effect transistor and the high electron mobility transistor (HEMT).
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] Initially, discrete transistors were embedded in stripline or microstrip circuits, but microwave integrated circuits followed.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] With these new devices, low-noise receiver preamplifiers became possible, which greatly increased the sensitivity, and hence the detection range, of DF systems.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] The DF receiver enjoys a detection range advantage over that of the radar receiver.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] This is because the signal strength at the DF receiver, due to a radar transmission, is proportional to 1/*R*2 whereas that at the radar receiver from the reflected return is proportional to *σ*/*R*4, where R is the range and σ is the radar cross-section of the DF system.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] This results in the signal strength at the radar receiver being very much smaller than that at the DF receiver.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] Consequently, in spite of its poor sensitivity, a simple crystal-video DF receiver is, usually, able to detect the signal transmission from a radar at a greater range than that at which the Radar's own receiver is able to detect the presence of the DF system.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] In practice, the advantage is reduced by the ratio of antenna gains (typically they are 36 dB and 10 dB for the Radar and ESM, respectively) and the use of Spread spectrum techniques, such as Chirp compression, by the Radar, to increase the processing gain of its receiver.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] On the other hand, the DF system can regain some advantage by using sensitive, low-noise, receivers and by using Stealth practices to reduce its radar cross-section, as with Stealth aircraft and Stealth ships.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] The move to microwave frequencies meant a reappraisal of the requirements of a DF system.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] Now, the receiver could no longer rely on a continuous signal stream on which to carry out measurements.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] Radars with their narrow beams would only illuminate the antennas of the DF system infrequently.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] Furthermore, some radars wishing to avoid detection (those of smugglers, hostile ships and missiles) would radiate their signals infrequently and often at low power.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] Such a system is referred to as a low-probability-of-intercept radar.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] In other applications, such as microwave links, the transmitter's antenna may never point at the DF receiver at all, so reception is only possible by means of the signal leakage from antenna side lobes.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] In addition, covert Data links may only radiate a high data rate sequence very occasionally.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p01] In general, in order to cater for modern circumstances, a broadband microwave DF system is required to have high sensitivity and have 360° coverage in order to have the ability to detect single pulses (often called amplitude monopulse) and achieve a high "Probability of Intercept" (PoI).
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p02] Amplitude comparison has been popular as a method for DF because systems are relatively simple to implement, have good sensitivity and, very importantly, a high probability of signal detection.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p02] Typically, an array of four, or more, squinted directional antennas is used to give 360 degree coverage.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p02] DF by phase comparison methods can give better bearing accuracy, but the processing is more complex.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p02] Systems using a single rotating dish antenna are more sensitive, small and relatively easy to implement, but have poor PoI.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p02] Usually, the signal amplitudes in two adjacent channels of the array are compared, to obtain the bearing of an incoming wavefront but, sometimes, three adjacent channels are used to give improved accuracy.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p02] Although the gains of the antennas and their amplifying chains have to be closely matched, careful design and construction and effective calibration procedures can compensate for shortfalls in the hardware.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p02] Overall bearing accuracies of 2° to 10° (rms) have been reported using the method.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p02] Two-channel DF, using two adjacent antennas of a circular array, is achieved by comparing the signal power of the largest signal with that of the second largest signal.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p02] The direction of an incoming signal, within the arc described by two antennas with a squint angle of Φ, may be obtained by comparing the relative powers of the signals received.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p02] When the signal is on the boresight of one of the antennas, the signal at the other antenna will be about 12 dB lower.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p02] When the signal direction is halfway between the two antennas, signal levels will be equal and approximately 3 dB lower than the boresight value.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p02] At other bearing angles, φ, some intermediate ratio of the signal levels will give the direction.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p02] To give 360° coverage, antennas of a circular array are chosen, in pairs, according to the signal levels received at each antenna.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p02] If there are N antennas in the array, at angular spacing (squint angle) Φ, then Φ = 2π/*N* radians (= 360/*N* degrees).
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p02] This shows the linear relationship between the output level difference, expressed logarithmically, and the bearing angle φ.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p02] Improvements in bearing accuracy may be achieved if amplitude data from a third antenna are included in the bearing processing.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p02] For three-channel DF, with three antennas squinted at angles Φ, the direction of the incoming signal is obtained by comparing the signal power of the channel containing the largest signal with the signal powers of the two adjacent channels, situated at each side of it.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p02] For the antennas in a circular array, three antennas are selected according to the signal levels received, with the largest signal present at the central channel.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p02] When the signal is on the boresight of Antenna 1 (*φ* = 0), the signal from the other two antennas will equal and about 12 dB lower.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p02] When the signal direction is halfway between two antennas (*φ* = 30°), their signal levels will be equal and approximately 3 dB lower than the boresight value, with the third signal now about 24 dB lower.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p02] At other bearing angles, φ, some intermediate ratios of the signal levels will give the direction.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p02] where GT is the overall gain of each channel, including antenna boresight gain, and is assumed to be the same in all three channels.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p02] As before, in these equations, angles are in radians, Φ = 360/*N* degrees = 2π/*N* radians and *A* = –ln(0.5).
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p02] The difference values here are in nepers but could be in decibels.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p02] The bearing value, obtained using this equation, is independent of the antenna beamwidth (= 2Ψ0), so this value does not have to be known for accurate bearing results to be obtained.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p02] Also, there is a smoothing affect, for bearing values near to the boresight of the middle antenna, so there is no discontinuity in bearing values there, as an incoming signals moves from left to right (or vice versa) through boresight, as can occur with 2-channel processing.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p02] Many of the causes of bearing error, such as mechanical imperfections in the antenna structure, poor gain matching of receiver gains, or non-ideal antenna gain patterns may be compensated by calibration procedures and corrective look-up tables, but thermal noise will always be a degrading factor.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p02] As all systems generate thermal noise then, when the level of the incoming signal is low, the signal-to-noise ratios in the receiver channels will be poor, and the accuracy of the bearing prediction will suffer.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p02] for a signal at crossover, but where SNR0 is the signal-to-noise ratio that would apply at boresight.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p02] To obtain more precise predictions at a given bearing, the actual S:N ratios of the signals of interest are used.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p02] (The results may be derived assuming that noise induced errors are approximated by relating differentials to uncorrelated noise).
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p02] For adjacent processing using, say, Channel 1 and Channel 2, the bearing uncertainty (angle noise), Δ*φ* (rms), is given below.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p02] In these results, square-law detection is assumed and the SNR figures are for signals at video (baseband), for the bearing angle φ.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p02] where SNR1 and SNR2 are the video (base-band) signal-to-noise values for the channels for Antenna 1 and Antenna 2, when square-law detection is used.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p02] where SNR1, SNR2 and SNR3 are the video signal-to-noise values for Channel 1, Channel 2, and Channel 3 respectively, for the bearing angle φ.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p02] A schematic of a possible DF system, employing six antennas, is shown in the figure.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p02] The signals received by the antennas are first amplified by a low-noise preamplifier before detection by detector-log-video-amplifiers (DLVAs).
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p02] The signal levels from the DLVAs are compared to determine the angle of arrival.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p02] By considering the signal levels on a logarithmic scale, as provided by the DLVAs, a large dynamic range is achieved and, in addition, the direction finding calculations are simplified when the main lobes of antenna patterns have a Gaussian characteristic, as shown earlier.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p02] A necessary part of the DF analysis is to identify the channel which contains the largest signal and this is achieved by means of a fast comparator circuit.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p02] In addition to the DF process, other properties of the signal may be investigated, such as pulse duration, frequency, pulse repetition frequency (PRF) and modulation characteristics.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p02] The comparator operation usually includes hysteresis, to avoid jitter in the selection process when the bearing of the incoming signal is such that two adjacent channels contain signals of similar amplitude.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p02] Often, the wideband amplifiers are protected from local high power sources (as on a ship) by input limiters and/or filters.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p02] Similarly the amplifiers might contain notch filters to remove known, but unwanted, signals which could impairs the system's ability to process weaker signals.
[src:aircraft-navigation/radio-direction-finder-p02] Some of these issues are covered in RF chain.
[src:aircraft-navigation/vhf-omnidirectional-range] VOR and the first DME(1950) system (referenced to 1950 since different from today's DME/N) to provide the slant range distance, were developed in the United States as part of a U.S. civil/military program for Aeronautical Navigation Aids in 1945.
[src:aircraft-navigation/vhf-omnidirectional-range] Deployment of VOR and DME(1950) began in 1949 by the U.S.
[src:aircraft-navigation/vhf-omnidirectional-range] ICAO standardized VOR and DME(1950) in 1950 in ICAO Annex, Edition 1.
[src:aircraft-navigation/vhf-omnidirectional-range] Frequencies for the use of VOR are standardized in the very high frequency (VHF) band between 108.00 and 117.95 MHz.
[src:aircraft-navigation/vhf-omnidirectional-range] To improve azimuth accuracy of VOR even under difficult siting conditions, Doppler VOR (DVOR) was developed in the 1960s.
[src:aircraft-navigation/vhf-omnidirectional-range] VOR is according to ICAO rules a *primary means navigation system* for commercial and general aviation, (D)VOR are gradually decommissioned and replaced by DME-DME RNAV (area navigation) 7.2.3 and satellite based navigation systems such as GPS in the early 21st century.
[src:aircraft-navigation/vhf-omnidirectional-range] In 2000 there were about 3,000 VOR stations operating around the world, including 1,033 in the US, but by 2013 the number in the US had been reduced to 967.
[src:aircraft-navigation/vhf-omnidirectional-range] The United States is decommissioning approximately half of its VOR stations and other legacy navigation aids as part of a move to performance-based navigation, while still retaining a "Minimum Operational Network" of VOR stations as a backup to GPS.
[src:aircraft-navigation/vhf-omnidirectional-range] In 2015, the UK started to reduce the number of stations from 44 to 19 which it completed in 2020.
[src:aircraft-navigation/vhf-omnidirectional-range] A VOR beacon radiates via two or more antennas an amplitude modulated signal and a frequency modulated subcarrier.
[src:aircraft-navigation/vhf-omnidirectional-range] By comparing the fixed 30 Hz reference signal with the rotating azimuth 30 Hz signal the azimuth from an aircraft to a (D)VOR is detected.
[src:aircraft-navigation/vhf-omnidirectional-range] The phase difference is indicative of the bearing from the (D)VOR station to the receiver relative to magnetic north.
[src:aircraft-navigation/vhf-omnidirectional-range] This line of position is called the VOR "radial".
[src:aircraft-navigation/vhf-omnidirectional-range] While providing the same signal over the air at the VOR receiver antennas.
[src:aircraft-navigation/vhf-omnidirectional-range] DVOR is based on the Doppler shift to modulate the azimuth dependent 30 Hz signal in space, by continuously switching the signal of about 25 antenna pairs that form a circle around the center 30 Hz reference antenna.
[src:aircraft-navigation/vhf-omnidirectional-range] The intersection of radials from two different VOR stations can be used to fix the position of the aircraft, as in earlier radio direction finding (RDF) systems.
[src:aircraft-navigation/vhf-omnidirectional-range] VOR stations are short range navigation aids limited to the radio-line-of-sight (RLOS) between transmitter and receiver in an aircraft.
[src:aircraft-navigation/vhf-omnidirectional-range] Depending on the site elevation of the VOR and altitude of the aircraft Designated Operational Coverages (DOC) of at max. about 200 nautical miles (370 kilometres) Att.C, Fig.C-13 can be achieved.
[src:aircraft-navigation/vhf-omnidirectional-range] The prerequisite is that the EIRP provides in spite of losses, e.g. due to propagation and antenna pattern lobing, for a sufficiently strong signal at the aircraft VOR antenna that it can be processed successfully by the VOR receiver.
[src:aircraft-navigation/vhf-omnidirectional-range] Each (D)VOR station broadcasts a VHF radio composite signal, including the mentioned navigation and reference signal, and a station's identifier and optional additional voice.
[src:aircraft-navigation/vhf-omnidirectional-range] 3.3.5 The station's identifier is typically a three-letter string in Morse code.
[src:aircraft-navigation/vhf-omnidirectional-range] While defined in Annex 10 voice channel is seldomly used today, e.g. for recorded advisories like ATIS.
[src:aircraft-navigation/vhf-omnidirectional-range] A **VORTAC** is a radio-based navigational aid for aircraft pilots consisting of a co-located VHF omnidirectional range and a tactical air navigation system (TACAN) beacon.
[src:aircraft-navigation/vhf-omnidirectional-range] Both types of beacons provide pilots azimuth information, but the VOR system is generally used by civil aircraft and the TACAN system by military aircraft.
[src:aircraft-navigation/vhf-omnidirectional-range] However, the TACAN distance measuring equipment is also used for civil purposes because civil DME equipment is built to match the military DME specifications.
[src:aircraft-navigation/vhf-omnidirectional-range] Most VOR installations in the United States are VORTACs.
[src:aircraft-navigation/vhf-omnidirectional-range] The system was designed and developed by the Cardion Corporation.
[src:aircraft-navigation/vhf-omnidirectional-range] The Research, Development, Test, and Evaluation (RDT&E) contract was awarded 28 December 1981.
[src:aircraft-navigation/vhf-omnidirectional-range] Luck filed a patent for a rotating radio beacon on behalf of RCA Corporation, which was issued in 1940.
[src:aircraft-navigation/vhf-omnidirectional-range] He followed that with two additional patents in 1940 for omnidirectional radio range.
[src:aircraft-navigation/vhf-omnidirectional-range] Previous radio beacons confined a pilot to a definite course, without information as to how far off course he may be.
[src:aircraft-navigation/vhf-omnidirectional-range] Luck described his radio range beacon as a radio lighthouse, "All this works like a lighthouse that sends out two kinds of light, one a beam that sweeps around steadily and the other a flash sent out in all directions just as the beam points north.
[src:aircraft-navigation/vhf-omnidirectional-range] Developed from earlier Visual Aural Radio Range (VAR) systems, the development of VOR was part of a U.S. civil/military program for aeronautical navigation aids.
[src:aircraft-navigation/vhf-omnidirectional-range] In 1949 VOR for the azimuth/bearing of an aircraft to/from a VOR installation and UHF DME(1950) and the first ICAO Distance Measuring Equipment standard, were put in operation by the U.S.
[src:aircraft-navigation/vhf-omnidirectional-range] In 1950 ICAO standardized VOR and DME(1950) in Annex 10 ed.1.
[src:aircraft-navigation/vhf-omnidirectional-range] The VOR was designed to provide 360 courses to and from the station, selectable by the pilot.
[src:aircraft-navigation/vhf-omnidirectional-range] Early vacuum tube transmitters with mechanically rotated antennas were widely installed in the 1950s, and began to be replaced with fully solid-state units in the early 1960s.
[src:aircraft-navigation/vhf-omnidirectional-range] DVOR was gradually implemented and became the major radio navigation system in the 1960s, when they took over from the older radio beacon and four-course (low/medium frequency range) system.
[src:aircraft-navigation/vhf-omnidirectional-range] Some of the older range stations survived, with the four-course directional features removed, as non-directional low or medium frequency radiobeacons (NDBs).
[src:aircraft-navigation/vhf-omnidirectional-range] A worldwide land-based network of "air highways", known in the US as Victor airways (below 18,000 ft or 5,500 m) and "jet routes" (at and above 18,000 feet), was set up linking VORs.
[src:aircraft-navigation/vhf-omnidirectional-range] VOR signals provide considerably greater accuracy and reliability than NDBs due to a combination of factors.
[src:aircraft-navigation/vhf-omnidirectional-range] Most significant is that VOR provides a bearing from the station to the aircraft which does not vary with wind or orientation of the aircraft.
[src:aircraft-navigation/vhf-omnidirectional-range] VHF radio is less vulnerable to diffraction (course bending) around terrain features and coastlines.
[src:aircraft-navigation/vhf-omnidirectional-range] Phase encoding suffers less interference from thunderstorms.
[src:aircraft-navigation/vhf-omnidirectional-range] VOR signals offer a predictable accuracy of 90 m (300 ft), 2 sigma at 2 NM from a pair of VOR beacons; as compared to the accuracy of unaugumented Global Positioning System (GPS) which is less than 13 meters, 95%.
[src:aircraft-navigation/vhf-omnidirectional-range] VOR stations, being VHF, operate on "line of sight".
[src:aircraft-navigation/vhf-omnidirectional-range] This means that if, on a perfectly clear day, you cannot see the transmitter from the receiver antenna, or vice versa, the signal will be either imperceptible or unusable.
[src:aircraft-navigation/vhf-omnidirectional-range] This limits VOR (and DME) range to the horizon—or closer if mountains intervene.
[src:aircraft-navigation/vhf-omnidirectional-range] Although the modern solid state transmitting equipment requires much less maintenance than the older units, an extensive network of stations, needed to provide reasonable coverage along main air routes, is a significant cost in operating current airway systems.
[src:aircraft-navigation/vhf-omnidirectional-range] Typically, a VOR station's identifier represents a nearby town, city or airport.
[src:aircraft-navigation/vhf-omnidirectional-range] For example, the VOR station located on the grounds of John F.
[src:aircraft-navigation/vhf-omnidirectional-range] Kennedy International Airport has the identifier JFK.
[src:aircraft-navigation/vhf-omnidirectional-range] VORs are assigned radio channels between 108.0 MHz and 117.95 MHz (with 50 kHz spacing); this is in the *very high frequency* (VHF) range.
[src:aircraft-navigation/vhf-omnidirectional-range] The first 4 MHz is shared with the instrument landing system (ILS) band.
[src:aircraft-navigation/vhf-omnidirectional-range] The VOR encodes azimuth (direction from the station) as the phase relationship between a reference signal and a variable signal.
[src:aircraft-navigation/vhf-omnidirectional-range] One of them is amplitude modulated, and one is frequency modulated.
[src:aircraft-navigation/vhf-omnidirectional-range] On conventional VORs (CVOR), the 30 Hz reference signal is frequency modulated (FM) on a 9,960 Hz subcarrier.
[src:aircraft-navigation/vhf-omnidirectional-range] On these VORs, the amplitude modulation is achieved by rotating a slightly directional antenna exactly in phase with the reference signal at 30 revolutions per second.
[src:aircraft-navigation/vhf-omnidirectional-range] Modern installations are Doppler VORs (DVOR), which use a circular array of typically 48 omnidirectional antennas and no moving parts.
[src:aircraft-navigation/vhf-omnidirectional-range] The active antenna is moved around the circular array electronically to create a doppler effect, resulting in frequency modulation.
[src:aircraft-navigation/vhf-omnidirectional-range] The amplitude modulated signal is transmitted from a separate omnidirectional antenna.
[src:aircraft-navigation/vhf-omnidirectional-range] The roles of amplitude and frequency modulation are thus swapped in this type of VOR.
[src:aircraft-navigation/vhf-omnidirectional-range] Decoding in the receiving aircraft happens in the same way for both types of VORs: the AM and FM 30 Hz components are detected and then compared to determine the phase angle between them.
[src:aircraft-navigation/vhf-omnidirectional-range] The VOR signal also contains a modulated continuous wave (MCW) 7 wpm Morse code station identifier, and usually contains an amplitude modulated (AM) voice channel.
[src:aircraft-navigation/vhf-omnidirectional-range] A radio magnetic indicator (RMI) features a course arrow superimposed on a rotating card that shows the aircraft's current heading at the top of the dial.
[src:aircraft-navigation/vhf-omnidirectional-range] The "tail" of the course arrow points at the current radial from the station and the "head" of the arrow points at the reciprocal (180° different) course to the station.
[src:aircraft-navigation/vhf-omnidirectional-range] An RMI may present information from more than one VOR or ADF receiver simultaneously.
[src:aircraft-navigation/vhf-omnidirectional-range] A horizontal situation indicator (HSI), developed subsequently to the RMI, is considerably more expensive and complex than a standard VOR indicator but combines heading information with the navigation display in a much more user-friendly format, approximating a simplified moving map.
[src:aircraft-navigation/vhf-omnidirectional-range] An area navigation (RNAV) system is an onboard computer with display and may include an up-to-date navigation database.
[src:aircraft-navigation/vhf-omnidirectional-range] At least one VOR/DME station is required for the computer to plot aircraft position on a moving map or to display course deviation and distance relative to a waypoint (virtual VOR station).
[src:aircraft-navigation/vhf-omnidirectional-range] RNAV type systems have also been made to use two VORs or two DMEs to define a waypoint; these are typically referred to by other names such as "distance computing equipment" for the dual-VOR type or "DME-DME" for the type using more than one DME signal.
[src:aircraft-navigation/vhf-omnidirectional-range] In many cases, VOR stations have co-located distance measuring equipment (DME) or military Tactical Air Navigation (TACAN) – the latter includes both the DME distance feature and a separate TACAN azimuth feature that provides military pilots data similar to the civilian VOR.
[src:aircraft-navigation/vhf-omnidirectional-range] A co-located VOR and TACAN beacon is called a VORTAC.
[src:aircraft-navigation/vhf-omnidirectional-range] A VOR co-located only with DME is called a VOR-DME.
[src:aircraft-navigation/vhf-omnidirectional-range] A VOR radial with a DME distance allows a one-station position fix.
[src:aircraft-navigation/vhf-omnidirectional-range] Both VOR-DMEs and TACANs share the same DME system.
[src:aircraft-navigation/vhf-omnidirectional-range] VORTACs and VOR-DMEs use a standardized scheme of VOR frequency to TACAN/DME channel pairing so that a specific VOR frequency is always paired with a specific co-located TACAN or DME channel.
[src:aircraft-navigation/vhf-omnidirectional-range] On civilian equipment, the VHF frequency is tuned and the appropriate TACAN/DME channel is automatically selected.
[src:aircraft-navigation/vhf-omnidirectional-range] While the operating principles are different, VORs share some characteristics with the localizer portion of ILS and the same antenna, receiving equipment and indicator is used in the cockpit for both.
[src:aircraft-navigation/vhf-omnidirectional-range] When a VOR station is selected, the OBS is functional and allows the pilot to select the desired radial to use for navigation.
